1. Nf3 Nf6 {We are going to build our repertoire starting with the move 1...
Nf6. This fits well with the Nimzo- or Bogo-Indian as after a subsequent d2-d4,
the game may transpose. If instead, we play 1...d5, White can play 2.d4, when
we end up in some line of the Queen's Gambit.  Now, White has two important
moves: 2.g3 and 2.c4.} 2. c4 ({After a "random" move like} 2. b3 {(or also 2.
d3 or 2.e3) it's a good idea to play a reversed London or Torre System. For
example} d5 3. Bb2 Bf5 4. e3 e6 {with a nice setup analogous to the London
System. We can do the same if White plays 1.b3 etc.}) (2. g3 d5 {Here we go
for the reversed Torre System.} 3. Bg2 c6 ({I prefer this to} 3... e6 4. O-O
Be7 5. c4 {when Black has to "suffer" in a Catalan type of position.}) 4. O-O
Bg4 {As a rule, Black gets a healthy, active position.} ({The reversed London} 
4... Bf5 {is playable, though I find 5.d3 a little annoying. Playing ...Bf5
would be good against a setup with d4 by White.})) 2... e6 {Against 2.c4 we
cannot go for the reversed Torre, so we try to reach positions in the spirit
of the Nimzo- or Bogo-Indian. After 2...e6 3.d4 we can directly transpos to
the Bogo-Indian with 3...Bb4+. Now, White's most popular moves are 3.g3 and 3.
Nc3.} 3. Nc3 (3. g3 a6 $5 {We choose 3...a6 - the variation invented by
legendary Grandmaster Oleg Romanishin.} (3... d5 {leads to the Catalan or
Reti-Catalan - extensive theoretical knowledge is needed...}) 4. Bg2 ({If
White prevents ...b5 with} 4. Nc3 {, Black switches to} d5 {Black threatens
both ...d4 and ...dxc4, which "forces"} 5. cxd5 exd5 {when we get the Karlsbad
Structure. White can argue, that now our move ...a6 was a waste of time, while
Black can argue that White normally does not Fianchetto his bishop in these
positions. A complicated strategic fight with chances for both sides is ahead.}
) 4... b5 {was proven to be viable for Black.}) 3... Bb4 {We have a
"Nimzo-Indian without d4". This should suit Nimzo-players, as the character of
the arising positions is similar to their favourite defence. We will go into
more detail in the theoretical section.} (3... d5 4. d4 {leads to a variation
of the Queen's Gambit Declined. Even here Black has a wide choice:} Bb4 {
(Ragosin)} (4... c5 {(Semi-Tarrasch)}) (4... c6 {(Semi-Slav)}) (4... dxc4 {
(Vienna-Variation)}) (4... Be7 {(QGD)}) (4... Z0 {- the list could be extended
by some sidelines.})) *

