{In this game, we see a typical strategy from White's point of view. Please
avoid the big mistake of allowing Nxg6, without White having had to weaken his
position with g3-g4 first!} 1. Nf3 $5 Nf6 2. g3 c6 3. Bg2 d5 4. O-O Bg4 {
Now, White can choose from playing various setups: d3, d4, c4, and the
non-dangerous double Fianchetto b3.} 5. d3 ({Against} 5. h3 {we almost always
play} Bh5 ({It is too early to give the bishop with} 5... Bxf3 $6 {For example}
6. Bxf3 e5 7. d3 Nbd7 8. e4 dxe4 {Against the pair of bishops, Black wants to
play a static position without pawn breaks. Still, White is better here; for
example:} (8... Be7 9. exd5 cxd5 10. c4 $1 $16 {Black has too many weaknesses
on the light squares.}) (8... d4 {Forget about this advance in the reverse
Torre! If we would have wanted to play ...d5-d4, we should have started with ..
.c5 (instead of ...c6) and developed our knight to c6.} 9. Bg2 c5 10. f4 $16 {
White has a perfect King's Indian setup, while Black's d7-knight is misplaced.}
) 9. dxe4 Be7 {Now White has some options; he only must avoid one thing:
exchanging his dark-squared bishop. The light-squared bishop is powerful, but
only if his colleague is still on the board!} 10. Bg2 (10. Nd2) (10. Be3 $6 Bc5
{Even now White should keep his bishop with a move like} 11. Bd2) 10... O-O 11.
Nd2 Qc7 12. Qe2 Rfe8 13. h4 {The light-squared bishop becomes very powerful as
it gets to h3. We may regret giving up our bishop for the f3-knight. White has
a very good position, which we want to avoid.})) 5... Nbd7 6. Nbd2 (6. c4 {
Whenever we see d3 in combination with c4, the best answer is to take it} dxc4
{, forcing} ({This move is playable, but after} 6... e6 7. cxd5 {White will
cause us some problems. We will study this positions under a different move
order.}) 7. dxc4 e5 {We get a symmetrical pawn structure with a very good and
healthy position for Black. For example} 8. Nc3 Bc5 9. Qc2 O-O 10. Rd1 Re8) ({
If White plays another move order with for example} 6. b3 e5 7. Bb2 Bd6 8. h3
Bh5 9. Nbd2 O-O 10. e4 {then Black can already keep the tension with} Re8 $1 {
We can at some point take on e4, but will choose an appropriate moment to do
so.} {For example, if White plays the mistake} 11. c4 $2 {, then} dxe4 12. dxe4
{is already very good for Black. The move c4 has created weaknesses on d4 and
d3, while also taking away the c4-square for his knight.} {A possible
continuation:} Qc7 13. a3 a5 14. Qc2 Bc5 15. Rfe1 Nf8 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Yf6d7,
Yf8e6] Black's idea is to play ...Nfd7 (to cover the e5-pawn), followed by ...
Ne6, focussing on the weakness of the d4-square.}) 6... e5 7. e4 dxe4 {We have
to take on e4.} ({Black would very much like to play} 7... Bd6 {, keeping the
tension.} {However, after} 8. h3 (8. exd5 cxd5 9. c4 d4 10. h3 Bh5 11. g4 Bg6
12. Nh4) 8... Bh5 9. exd5 $1 cxd5 10. c4 $1 {White has good chances for an
advantage.}) 8. dxe4 (8. Nxe4 Nxe4 9. dxe4 Be7 $11) 8... Be7 9. h3 Bh5 {
We never take on f3, unless we win something.} 10. Qe1 ({If White wants to
exchange our bishop immediately by playing} 10. g4 Bg6 11. Nh4 {the weakness
of the f4-square gives Black a very good position.} O-O 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. Qe2 {
White would very much like to play the illegal g4-g3, when he would be better!}
Nc5 14. Nb3 Ne6 $17 {Maybe next, Black can play ...Nd7 followed by ...Bg5.})
10... O-O 11. Nh4 Re8 12. Nb3 ({After} 12. Bf3 {we will definitely not play}
Bg6 $2 13. Nxg6 hxg6 {After for example} 14. Nb3 a5 15. a4 Nc5 16. Nxc5 Bxc5
17. Kg2 Qc7 18. Bd2 {[%csl Gd2,Gf3][%cal Ya1d1,Yd2c1,Yh3h4,Yf1h1] White has
maybe an only small advantage, but it's permanent.}) 12... a5 13. a4 Nc5 14.
Qe3 Nfd7 15. Nf5 Bf8 16. Bf3 Bg6 $2 ({Black should have taken on f3} 16... Bxf3
17. Qxf3 Ne6 {with an equal position.} 18. Be3 Qc7 $11) 17. Nh4 Nxb3 18. Qxb3
Nc5 19. Qe3 Qc7 20. Nxg6 hxg6 21. Qe2 $1 {White can use the c4-square for his
queen.} Ne6 22. c3 Bc5 23. h4 $1 $16 {Developing the c1-bishop is not a
priority as it already takes part in the game.} (23. Be3 $2 {would give away
White's advantage. He should not exchange bishops!} Bxe3 24. Qxe3 $11) 23...
Rad8 24. Kg2 Rd6 25. Rh1 {White is looking for a good moment to attack with
h4-h5. Later he won a nice game.} Qe7 26. Bg4 $1 Qf6 27. h5 gxh5 (27... g5 28.
Bf5 (28. Qf3 Qxf3+ 29. Kxf3 $14) 28... Red8 29. Qg4 $16) 28. Rxh5 g6 29. Rh1
Ng5 30. Rf1 Red8 31. f4 Ne6 32. f5 Ng5 33. fxg6 Qxg6 34. Rf5 Ne6 35. Bh5 Qg7
36. Bxf7+ Qxf7 37. Rxf7 Kxf7 38. Qh5+ Ke7 39. Qh7+ Ke8 40. Qh5+ Kd7 41. Qxe5
Rg8 42. Bf4 Rd3 43. Qf5 Ke7 44. Rh1 Rg7 45. Rh6 Nxf4+ 46. Qxf4 Bd6 47. Qf6+ 1-0

