{An amazing high-level game by Wang Hao. Study how he handles his pieces with
exceptional skill while managing to play the Nxg6 idea!} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 d5 3.
Bg2 c6 4. O-O Bg4 5. c4 e6 ({To take on c4 now} 5... dxc4 {is an entirely
different story than 5...e6 6.d3 dxc4. White will take back the c4-pawn with a
piece.} 6. Na3 Nbd7 (6... b5 {Defending the pawn in this way does not fit with
...Bg4.} 7. Ne5 Bd7 8. Nxb5 $18) 7. Nxc4 e6 8. d3 {Strengthening the light
squares is much better than playing d4.} Be7 9. Bd2 O-O 10. b4 {Black can
hardly find a good plan.} Re8 11. Qb3 Rc8 12. a4 $16 {White is improving his
position and later will play b5. He might also start using his pawn majority
in the center.}) 6. d3 (6. cxd5 Bxf3 $1 7. Bxf3 cxd5 8. Nc3 Nc6 $11 {[%csl Gc6]
}) 6... dxc4 $1 {This is the correct reaction for Black! White is forced to
take back on c4 with the pawn.} 7. dxc4 Nbd7 $5 {this is equally good with
Qxd1 ...just a matter of taste!} (7... Qxd1 $5 8. Rxd1 Nbd7 $11 9. Be3 (9. Nc3
Bb4 $5 (9... O-O-O $5 $132) 10. Bd2 O-O-O 11. a3 Be7 $132) 9... Bc5 10. Bxc5
Nxc5 11. Nc3 $2 {A very nice positional exercise: what should Black play? I
showed this to my students and some also some high-level players.} (11. b4 $142
$132) 11... Bxf3 $1 $15 (11... a5 {preventing b4, allows} 12. Ne5 {[%csl Rg4]})
12. Bxf3 a5 {Only now - Black is already better since White's bishop is quite
useless.} 13. Rd2 Rd8 {To get the maximum out of the position we should
exchange ONE rook.} 14. Rad1 Rxd2 15. Rxd2 Ke7 16. e3 g5 {We keep one rook on
the board and start attacking on the kingside. The d-file is no longer
important as all entry squares are firmly covered.}) 8. Nc3 Qc7 9. h3 Bh5 10.
Nh4 Be7 11. Bf4 $1 {An interesting move by White - after provoking e5 the
h4-knight gets access to f5.} e5 12. Bg5 Bg6 $2 {Caruana was afraid of a
knight coming to f5.} (12... O-O 13. Nf5 Rfe8) 13. Nxg6 hxg6 14. Qc2 Nc5 15.
Rad1 Ne6 16. Bc1 $1 Nd4 (16... O-O $1 $14) 17. Qa4 Nd7 18. Rd2 $3 Nc5 19. Qd1
a5 20. e3 Nde6 21. Nd5 $3 cxd5 $2 (21... Qb8 $1 22. Nxe7 Kxe7 23. b3 $14) 22.
cxd5 $16 Ng5 23. h4 Qd6 24. hxg5 Bxg5 25. b3 $1 Nd7 26. a4 $3 O-O 27. Ra2 $3
Nc5 28. Ba3 Be7 29. Rc2 Rac8 30. Qe2 Qb6 31. Rfc1 Bd6 32. Qg4 $1 Qa7 33. Bf3 $3
b6 34. Kg2 Rfe8 35. Rh1 Qe7 36. e4 Nd7 37. Rxc8 Rxc8 38. Qh3 f5 39. Bxd6 1-0

