{A nice blitz game of mine, demonstrating, that the Double-Fianchetto system
is actually harmless for Black!} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 c6 4. O-O Bg4 5. b3
Nbd7 6. Bb2 e6 {With this move order, we have to lose a tempo if we later play
...e5, but that's not a big problem.} ({If we prepare ...e5 with} 6... Qc7 {
then our queen might become exposed on the c-file:} 7. c4 e5 8. cxd5 cxd5 9.
Nc3 {[%csl Gc1,Rc7][%cal Ya1c1,Yc1c7]}) 7. d3 Bd6 8. Nbd2 O-O 9. e4 e5 $1 {
Now we do not release the tension in the center!} 10. h3 Bh5 11. g4 (11. c4
dxe4 $3 12. dxe4 Qc7 {xd4 !}) 11... Bg6 $15 12. Re1 Re8 {Black will at some
point take on d4, but for the moment I keep the tension.} (12... a5 {is
automatically answered by} 13. a3 {so that after} a4 $6 {White can play} 14. b4
) 13. a4 $6 {A typical mistake, which is punished by} (13. Nh4 {can be
answered by} Qc7 ({Black can also play} 13... dxe4 {For example} 14. Nxg6 hxg6
15. dxe4 Qc7 16. Nc4 Bb4 17. c3 Bf8 {[%csl Ge6,Rf4][%cal Yd7c5,Yc5e6] Black is
already better since the g2-bishop is terrible and there are weaknesses on the
dark squares.}) {After the greedy} 14. Nxg6 hxg6 15. g5 Nh5 16. exd5 cxd5 17.
Bxd5 Nf4 {Black gets tremendous compensation.}) 13... Bb4 $1 {Nepomniachtchi
committed the same mistake with colours reversed in Kramnik-Nepomniachtchi
where White played the Torre Attack. Check out this game!} 14. Re2 ({If White
plays} 14. c3 {I proudly go back} Bf8 {and will go for the weak d3-square with
...Nc5.}) 14... dxe4 {Black now took on e4 - there is no concrete rule of when
exactly to do this. We need to decide ourselves!} 15. Nxe4 Nxe4 16. dxe4 Qc7 {
Black is already better due to the weaknesses on the dark squares.} 17. Nh4
Rad8 18. Nxg6 hxg6 19. Qf1 Nf8 {The knight is coming to e6 from where it
targets the weak squares.} 20. Re3 Ne6 21. Qc4 Bc5 22. Rd3 Rxd3 23. cxd3 Bd4
24. Bxd4 Nxd4 {Black has a strategically won game.} 25. Kf1 g5 26. b4 a6 27.
Rc1 Qd7 28. a5 Re6 29. Re1 Qd6 30. Kg1 g6 31. Kf1 Kg7 32. Re3 Re7 33. Re1 Rd7
34. Rd1 Qf6 35. Rd2 Qf4 36. Qc3 Nb5 37. Qb2 Rd4 38. Ke2 Qf6 39. Bf1 Qd6 40. Ke1
Rxb4 41. Qa1 Nd4 0-1

