{Another good blitz game by me - punishing the combination of the pawn moves
e4-c4 by White! The d4-square becomes weak!} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 c6 4.
O-O Bg4 5. d3 Nbd7 6. Nbd2 e5 7. c4 {The combination of the moves Nbd2 and c4
is quite rare.} Bd6 {Due to the passive position of the d2-knight, we can keep
the tension.} ({Here we don't play} 7... dxc4 $2 {because White can play} 8.
Nxc4) 8. b3 ({In case of} 8. cxd5 cxd5 {White has no longer the option of Nc3.}
) 8... O-O 9. Bb2 Re8 10. e4 $2 dxe4 11. dxe4 (11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. dxe4 Qc7 $15 {
[%csl Gc5,Rd4,Ge6][%cal Yd6c5,Yd7f8,Yf8e6]}) 11... Nc5 12. Qc2 {White is
threatening b4 followed by c5, when his knight gets access to the great
c4-square. We should of course prevent this:} a5 $1 (12... Qc7 $2 13. b4 Ncd7
14. c5 Bf8 15. Nc4 $36) 13. h3 Bxf3 $1 {A good move - we want to win control
over the d4-square.} 14. Bxf3 {Unfortunately White cannot take back with the
knight, since then e4 would be lost.} Qc7 15. Bg2 Ne6 16. Rad1 Bc5 17. Nb1 Nd4
18. Bxd4 Bxd4 $17 {Black is much better - his bishop is much more active than
the one on g2.} 19. Nc3 Rad8 20. Ne2 Bc5 21. Rxd8 Rxd8 22. Rd1 g6 23. Rd3 Rxd3
24. Qxd3 Nd7 {[%csl Gc5,Rd4,Ge6,Rg2][%cal Yd7f8,Yf8e6]} 25. Nc3 Nf8 26. h4 Ne6
27. Ne2 {In a standard game I would probably play ...Qb6 or ...Bd4, but ...Nd4
is also not bad.} Nd4 28. Nxd4 Bxd4 29. h5 Qd6 30. Qf3 Kg7 31. Bh3 Qe7 32. Kg2
Qg5 33. hxg6 hxg6 34. Qg4 $2 {Now I started collecting pawns and later I won
the game.} Qd2 35. Qf3 Qxa2 36. Bd7 Qa3 37. Bc8 Qe7 38. Qg4 b5 39. cxb5 cxb5
40. Qd7 Qf6 41. f4 exf4 42. e5 Qxe5 43. Bb7 fxg3 44. Bf3 Qe3 45. Kh3 Qf2 46.
Kg4 g2 47. Qxd4+ Qxd4+ 0-1

