1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 Bg4 (3... c6 {is a little bit more accurate.} 4. O-O
Bg4 {If White goes for the Double Fianchetto now, then} 5. b3 Nbd7 6. Bb2 ({
White may try} 6. Ba3 e5 7. Bxf8 Kxf8 {, though losing the right to castle is
not a big deal for Black. For example} 8. d3 (8. h3 Bxf3 {Here we can give up
our g4-bishop, since White does not have the pair of bishops.} 9. Bxf3 g6 10.
d3 Kg7) 8... Bxf3 {I would probably even exchange the bishops now. White's
light-squared bishop is only good if it's colleague - the dark-squared bishop
- is on the board.} 9. Bxf3 g6 10. e4 dxe4 {Simply taking on e4 leads to a
good position for Black.} 11. dxe4 Kg7 {Black is slightly better.}) 6... e6 $11
{[%cal Yf8d6,Ye8g8]}) 4. O-O Nbd7 5. d4 {This is a new move for us - until now
we have analyzed setups with d3.} e6 6. c4 c6 7. Qb3 ({Again, White can go for
a Double Fianchetto, when Black's position is very healthy. For example:} 7. b3
Be7 {I believe that ...Be7 is slightly more accurate in this position.} (7...
Bd6 8. Bb2 O-O 9. Nbd2 b5 {With the bishop on d6, White has the annoying move}
10. Ne5 $1 {With the bishop on e7, Black could simply play 10...Nxe5, which
now loses a piece.} Rc8 11. Nxg4 Nxg4 12. e4 $18 {[%cal Yd1g4]}) 8. Bb2 O-O 9.
Nbd2 h6 {Preparing ...Bf5.} (9... Bf5 {can be met with} 10. Nh4 $1 Bg4 $5 {
If White still wants to exchange our bishop, he at least has to weaken himself
with g4.} (10... Bg6 {leads to a risk-free advantage for White.} 11. Nxg6 hxg6
12. e4 $14 {For example,} dxe4 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 Nf6 15. Bf3 Qc7 16. Qe2
Rad8 17. Kg2 Rfe8 18. h4) 11. h3 Bh5 12. g4 Bg6) ({Also playable is} 9... a5
10. a3 b5 {Now Ne5 poses no problem:} 11. Ne5 Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd7)) (7. Nbd2 Be7
8. cxd5 $2 (8. b3 {see 7.b3.}) 8... exd5 {Here Black is already slightly
better. White should take on d5 only when he has some specific idea in mind.})
7... Qb6 (7... Rb8 $2 8. Bf4 $18) 8. c5 (8. Qxb6 $2 {This is a mistake, after
which Black is already better.} axb6 9. cxd5 exd5) 8... Qa6 $1 {This is the
right idea in such positions - ...Qa6, followed by a fast ...b7-b6!. After
cxb6, we take back with ...axb6! (or ...Qxb6 both are good!).} 9. Nc3 b6 $1 10.
cxb6 axb6 11. Bf4 Be7 12. Rfc1 O-O {Black has completed his development and is
doing great. Later he won the game.} 13. e3 Rfc8 14. Ne5 Nxe5 15. Bxe5 Nd7 16.
h3 Bf5 17. g4 Bd3 18. Bg3 c5 19. dxc5 bxc5 20. Qd1 c4 21. Bf1 Nc5 22. Bxd3 Nxd3
23. Rc2 Bf6 24. Rb1 Qa5 25. a3 Ra7 26. Ne2 Rc6 27. Nf4 Nxf4 28. Bxf4 Rb7 29.
Qc1 h6 30. b3 Rcb6 0-1

