{A good online rapid game - demonstrating how to use typical dark square
weaknesses in White's position.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 c6 4. g3 (4. e3 Bf5
{leads to a reversed London System.} (4... Bg4 {is also fine.})) 4... Bg4 5.
Bg2 Nbd7 6. d3 e6 (6... Bxf3 $6 7. Bxf3 e5 8. e4 $14) 7. Nbd2 Bd6 8. O-O O-O 9.
e4 e5 {I keep the tension in the center and will later decide when to take on
e4. I evaluate the position as already slightly better for Black.} 10. h3 Bh5
11. exd5 cxd5 12. Re1 Re8 13. g4 Bg6 14. Nh4 Rc8 {"Simple developing moves,
whenever they are possible!" "Help your pieces, so that they can help you!"}
15. Nxg6 hxg6 16. c4 Nc5 {Threatening to take on d3.} 17. Qe2 Ne6 {My knight
is going to f4 with devastating effect.} 18. Qf1 Nf4 19. Nf3 e4 {I had to
calculate the consequences of this move.} 20. dxe4 dxe4 21. Bxf6 gxf6 {I take
with the pawn to be able to support my e-pawn with ...f5.} 22. Nh2 f5 23. Rad1
Qf6 $19 {Black has a winning position. White is playing without his knight and
without his bishop on g2.} 24. Re3 Rcd8 25. gxf5 gxf5 26. Rg3+ Kf8 27. Kh1 Bc5
28. Rxd8 Rxd8 29. Qc1 Nd3 30. Rxd3 exd3 31. Bd5 Qh4 32. Qc3 Re8 33. Nf3 Qxh3+
34. Kg1 Bxf2+ 35. Kxf2 Re2+ 36. Kg1 Qg2# 0-1

