{A wonderful game by Black! If White prevents ...b5 by 4.Nc3, Black answers 4..
.d5, which typically leads to the Carlsbad structure.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3.
g3 a6 4. Nc3 (4. Qc2 d5 5. Qc3 Be7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O c6 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Qc2)
4... d5 $1 {Now we threaten ...d4 or ...dxc4.} 5. cxd5 (5. d4 dxc4 {is quite
good for Black - with the knight on c3 it is not easy to regain the pawn.} 6.
Qa4+ $2 b5 $1 7. Nxb5 $2 Bd7 $19) 5... exd5 6. Bg2 Bd6 7. O-O O-O {Now White
has to choose between d3 and d4.} 8. d4 ({In my opinion the best move is} 8. d3
{with the idea to play e4. Here we should not play ...c6. For example} h6 9. e4
dxe4 10. dxe4 Nc6 {and Black is doing ok.}) 8... Nbd7 {This is in fact a
reversed Caro-Kann!} ({I like} 8... c6 {with the idea} 9. Bf4 Bxf4 10. gxf4 Ne8
$1 {[%cal Ye8d6] even better.} 11. Ne5 Nd6 $15) 9. Bf4 Bxf4 10. gxf4 Nb6 ({Or} 
10... c6 11. Ne5 Ne8 12. Nxd7 Bxd7 13. Rc1 Nd6 $17) 11. Ne5 Bf5 12. Rc1 Ne4 13.
e3 Nxc3 14. Rxc3 c6 15. Kh1 f6 16. Nf3 (16. Nd3 Bxd3 17. Qxd3 f5 $1 $15 {
For example} (17... Nc4 18. e4 $1 $132) 18. Rb3 Rb8 19. Rc3 Nc8 20. Bf3 Nd6 21.
Rg1 Rf6) 16... Nc4 17. Nh4 Nd6 18. Nxf5 Nxf5 19. Bh3 Nd6 $15 20. f5 Qe7 21. f3
Kh8 22. Re1 Rae8 23. Qd3 Qf7 24. Bg4 g6 $3 $17 (24... g5 $5) 25. fxg6 (25. Rc2
gxf5 26. Bxf5 Qh5 27. Bg4 Qh4 28. Rf1 f5 $19) 25... Qxg6 $6 (25... hxg6 $142
26. e4 f5 $19) 26. Qxg6 (26. Qe2 f5 27. Bh3 Qh5 $19) 26... hxg6 $17 27. Bh3 Rf7
28. Kg1 Rfe7 29. b3 f5 30. f4 Ne4 31. Rc2 Kg7 32. Bg2 Kf6 (32... Nf6 33. Rce2
Ng4 34. Bf3 Kf6 $19) 33. Bxe4 Rxe4 34. Rce2 g5 35. fxg5+ Kxg5 36. Rg2+ Kf6 37.
Rge2 a5 38. Kf2 f4 39. Kf3 Kf5 $19 40. h3 fxe3 41. Rxe3 Rf4+ 42. Kg3 (42. Ke2
Rxe3+ 43. Kxe3 Re4+ $19) 42... Rxe3+ 43. Rxe3 Rxd4 44. Re7 Rd3+ 45. Kh4 b5 46.
Ra7 a4 47. bxa4 Rd4+ 48. Kg3 Rxa4 49. Rc7 Ra3+ 50. Kh4 Rc3 0-1

