-34,-120,-119,-125,-23,-166,-88,-88,-97,-180,-180,-186,-173,-183,-183,-257,
-257,-257,-184,-183,-138,-143,-160,-182,-358,-358,-349,-612,-643]} 1. c4 e5 2.
Nc3 Bb4 {Our chosen variation, it has been popularized by Vishy Anand. The
plan is to take on c3 and then continue with ...d6 and ...f5!} 3. e3 $2 {
This move simply allows doubled pawns and it is probably the worst choice.}
Bxc3 4. bxc3 d6 5. d4 c5 6. Nf3 (6. dxe5 dxe5 7. Qd5 {White wants to undouble
his pawns, but we aren't forced to capture it.} Qe7 8. Ba3 Nd7 {simply
defending the pawn. White's queen on d5 will give us some tempo's to complete
development.} 9. Nf3 Ngf6 10. Qd1 b6 {Followed by Bb7, Black is already better.
}) (6. d5 f5 {typical play!} 7. Bd3 Nf6 8. Ne2 g6 9. O-O Kd7 {We wish to
safeguard our King on c7 and develop and attack on kingside pretty soon.}) 6...
e4 7. Nd2 f5 8. Nb3 Qc7 9. Qh5+ g6 10. Qg5 b6 11. Be2 Qe7 12. h4 Nd7 13. Ba3
Ba6 14. O-O-O O-O-O 15. Qf4 Ngf6 16. Rhe1 Rhe8 17. Kc2 Qf7 18. Nd2 Qe6 19. Bf1
Nb8 20. f3 Qd7 21. Qg5 Qa4+ 22. Kb2 Nbd7 23. Qf4 Nh5 24. Qh2 Ndf6 25. g4 exf3
26. gxh5 Ng4 27. Qf4 f2 28. hxg6 hxg6 29. h5 fxe1=Q 30. Rxe1 gxh5 31. Bd3 Kc7
32. Bxf5 Bc8 33. Bc2 Qc6 34. Qg5 Qg2 35. Kc1 Nxe3 36. Qxh5 Nxc4 0-1

