{This lecture features the position arising after} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2
c6 {[%cal Gc8g4] Against the Reti, I like to play the reversed Torre setup. It
is an independent system, which means you can play it even if you play kings
Indian, Grunfeld, Nimzo, or Slav. You can always employ it against this move
order.  In this position, White has three logical ways to continue  1) Early
c2-c4  2) Setups with d2-d3  3) Setups with d2-d4 Against all these options,
you can play just by applying the correct plans and ideas. Concrete theory is
not required.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "2024.05.02"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Reversed torre"]
[Black "Theory"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D02"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "34"]
[EventDate "2019.11.28"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 c6 $1 {Against the Reti, I like to play the
reversed torre setup. It is an independent system, which means you can play it
even if you play kings Indian, Grunfeld, nimzo, or Slav. You can always employ
it against this move order. In this position, White has three logical ways to
continue 1) Early c4 2) Setups with d2-d3 3) Setups with d2-d4} 4. O-O (4. d3
$5 {White can also first play short-side casting it just transposes. We plan
to play Bg4-Nbd7-e5} Bg4 5. O-O Nbd7 (5... e6 $5 {is also playable.} 6. h3 Bh5
7. Nbd2 Be7 8. e4 O-O 9. Qe1 a5 $1 $132 {You are welcome to explore this on
your own.}) 6. Nbd2 e5 7. e4 dxe4 $1 (7... Bd6 $6 8. exd5 cxd5 9. c4 $3 $36 {
And suddenly White is better. So, we should always take on e4 first.}) 8. dxe4
Qc7 $5 {the most flexible move. Black can play Be7/Bc5 in the future. Again no
concrete theory is needed and this opening is played on middlegame plans. The
following moves display those plans.} 9. h3 Bh5 10. b3 Be7 11. Bb2 O-O 12. Qe1
Rfe8 13. Nh4 (13. a4 Bb4 {a very annoying move to face.} 14. Ba3 Bxa3 {Black
is in good shape.}) 13... Bf8 14. Kh2 Nc5 15. a3 Nfd7 16. Qe3 f6 17. Bf3 Bf7
18. Rad1 b5 {with a good position.}) 4... Bg4 5. d4 $5 {Another important
set-up. We should make sure to develop the knight on b8 only after playing the
important move h7-h6.} (5. c4 $5 {This is tricky to move order to phase. White
wants to respond to dxc4 with Na3-Nxc4.} e6 $1 (5... dxc4 $2 6. Na3 e6 7. Nxc4
Nbd7 8. d3 $16 {Black looks solid but his pieces are not active.}) 6. cxd5 Bxf3
$3 {A clever intermezzo! The point is to avoid d3-Nc3-e4 setups which are
annoying to face after we capture exd5.} 7. Bxf3 cxd5 $1 {The point is there
are no Ne5 attacks. Our position is pretty solid and we will start fighting
for initiative soon.} 8. Qb3 Qd7 $1 {Black has pretty simple plans of
Nc6-Be7-0-0-Rfc8 etc.}) 5... e6 $1 {Planning Be7. Note: In such positions, our
Bishop is better placed on e7.} 6. h3 $1 (6. Nbd2 $1 {White is trying to go
for e4. Now, both Nbd7 & Be7 are good.} Be7 $1 (6... Nbd7 $1 7. Re1 Be7 8. e4
h6 $3 $132 {planning to keep the knight on h7 instead of e8.} (8... O-O {
We wish to avoid the move ...Ne8 after e5.}) 9. e5 Nh7 {Black has a good
position with Ng5 ideas in the air.}) 7. Re1 O-O 8. e4 Bh5 $5 {Not just a
clever waiting move, we also set up a positional trap which will be
demonstrated in a moment.} 9. c3 (9. e5 $2 {This is probably the worst version
for White.} Nfd7 10. c3 c5 11. h3 Nc6 $17 {Black has the best version of
carokann.}) (9. h3 $1 {White is planning the usual g4-Nh4. The only plan to
remember in this line is that we don't want our knight on e8 and instead would
like to keep on h7 or d7.} h6 $1 {Preparing against e5.} 10. e5 (10. g4 Bg6 11.
Ne5 Bxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 dxe4 14. Rxe4 Nd7 {with equality. White has
weakened himself a bit too much.}) (10. c3 {White waits for us again. But now,
we can conclude this by playing} Nbd7 11. e5 Nh7 {with no problems whatsoever.}
) 10... Nfd7 {Please note, that we always prefer the square d7 over h7 because
it's closer to the center.} 11. c3 c5 12. Nf1 Nc6 13. g4 Bg6 14. Ng3 Rc8 15. a3
b5 $17 {Black has good counterplay on queen while White tries to attack on the
kingside. It is a complex position with chances for both sides.}) 9... h6 $1 {
the waiting game continues.} 10. h3 Nbd7 11. e5 Nh7 $1 $132 {Black has good
play.}) (6. Ne5 Bh5 7. c4 Nbd7 8. Nc3 Be7 9. Qb3 Nxe5 $3 10. dxe5 Nd7 $36 {
The above continuation is forced to get a good position. So make sure you
memorize it.}) 6... Bh5 7. c4 $1 {A very tricky setup, White forces our Bishop
to h5 and wants to play cxd5-exd5 Nh4! Aiming for Nf5 ideas. What is the
solution? The simplest solution is to play Bg6 whenever you see Nh4 and it
transposes into a better carokann for Black.} Be7 $1 8. cxd5 (8. Qb3 {White
wants to pressurize the b7-pawn. We always reply with ...Qb6 not fearing the
doubled pawns.} Qb6 9. c5 Qa6 $3 {A very nice strategy aiming for ...b6 next.}
10. Nc3 Nbd7 11. Bf4 b6 12. cxb6 axb6 $132 {with decent play for Black.}) (8.
Nc3 Nbd7 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Nh4 Bg6 {Always remmember to respond to Nf5 threats
with ...Bg6!}) 8... exd5 $1 9. Nh4 Bg6 $1 10. Nc3 Nbd7 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. b3 O-O
13. Bb2 Re8 14. e3 Bb4 $3 {We wish to establish control the e4-square.} 15. a3
Bxc3 $3 {The computer wants to give up the pair of Bishops for a kingside
attack.} 16. Bxc3 Ne4 17. Bb2 g5 $17 {with good attacking chances.} *

