1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 c6 $1 4. c4 $1 Bf5 $5 {in my view , the most active
move here!} 5. Qb3 $1 {A very dangerous system to face as Black. White get's a
very small annoying edge in the end however our pieces are more active.} (5.
cxd5 $6 {A typical mistake among lower rated players.} cxd5 6. Qb3 Nc6 $3 7.
Qxb7 Bd7 8. Qb3 e5 $1 {This is a good moment to stop. Black has a huge center
control and development edge over a small pawn.}) (5. O-O e6 6. d3 dxc4 $3 {
We always take on c4 in such structures.} 7. dxc4 Qxd1 $132 {with an even
position.}) (5. b3 $6 {The double frianchatoo is very lame.} e6 6. Bb2 Nbd7 7.
O-O h6 $5 {Saving the Bishop against Nh4 threats. Black is better.}) 5... Qb6
6. d3 (6. cxd5 $6 {is very hasty.} Qxb3 $1 7. axb3 cxd5 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. Nh4 Be6
$15 {Black has weakened his queenside for no reason.}) (6. Qxb6 $6 axb6 7. cxd5
Nxd5 $3 {important move not leaving the b6,b7 pawns alone. Black is okay.})
6... e6 7. Be3 Qa6 $1 {A good choice if you wish to solid lines with queen
trades.} 8. cxd5 $5 (8. O-O $6 dxc4 $1 {White has slowed down a little and
this is the time to strike.}) (8. Nc3 $6 dxc4 9. Qxc4 Qxc4 10. dxc4 Nbd7 11.
Nd4 Bg6 $15 {Black is very solid with no weak points.}) (8. Nh4 $6 {hoping to
get the pair bishops.} dxc4 9. dxc4 Be4 $132 10. O-O Bxg2 11. Kxg2 Nbd7 $11 {
with usual play.}) (8. Nbd2 $5 h6 $5 9. O-O Nbd7 {Once against a simple
position to play.}) 8... exd5 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Nc3 Bc5 $132 {Following up with
castle we have a pleasant position.} *

