1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 c6 4. c4 Bf5 (4... Bg4 {I found this to be
inconsisent here because of} 5. O-O e6 6. d4 Nbd7 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Qb3 Qb6 9.
Qe3+ Be7 10. h3 Bh5 11. Nh4 Bg6 12. Nc3 Qd8 13. Nxg6 hxg6 {Where White has
some dynamic chances and we have to learn lots of theory.}) 5. O-O e6 6. cxd5
exd5 7. d3 Bc5 (7... h6 $2 8. e4 {This is White's plan.}) 8. Qb3 $5 Bb6 9. Nc3
(9. Qa3 $5 {This is an interesting approach by White to stop castling. It can
be answered with} Na6 $1 10. e4 dxe4 11. dxe4 Be6 $15 {followed by Bc5.}) 9...
O-O 10. Na4 Nbd7 11. Nxb6 axb6 12. Qc2 Bg4 (12... b5 {makes a lot of sense.
The game can continue as} 13. b3 b4 14. Bb2 h6 15. a3 bxa3 16. Rxa3 Rxa3 17.
Bxa3 Re8 $132 {with chances for both sides.}) 13. e4 $6 (13. b3 {White is
planning Bb2 to pressurize the a1-h8 diagonal.} Re8 14. Bb2 b5 15. a3 h6 16.
Rfe1 Qb6 17. Rac1 $132 {And this leads to another low theory position for us
to try out.}) 13... Re8 $15 14. Re1 dxe4 15. dxe4 Nc5 16. Rd1 Qc8 17. e5 Bxf3
18. Bxf3 Rxe5 19. Bf4 Re8 20. b4 Nce4 21. Re1 Qf5 22. Re2 Re6 23. Rd1 g6 24.
Kg2 Rae8 25. a4 g5 26. Be3 g4 27. Bxe4 Rxe4 28. Red2 Qf3+ 29. Kg1 Nd5 30. b5
Nxe3 31. fxe3 Rxe3 32. Rf1 Re1 33. Rdf2 Rxf1+ 34. Rxf1 Qe3+ 35. Rf2 Qd4 36. Qf5
Re1+ 37. Kg2 Qe4+ 38. Qxe4 Rxe4 39. Rf6 Rxa4 40. bxc6 bxc6 41. Rxc6 Ra2+ 42.
Kg1 Rb2 43. Rc4 h5 44. h3 gxh3 45. Rh4 Rg2+ 46. Kh1 Rxg3 47. Rb4 Rg6 0-1

