{[%evp 0,86,18,18,18,15,25,13,32,7,18,15,15,15,15,21,19,19,22,22,31,15,34,27,
16,16,16,9,5,9,9,9,3,-6,18,6,-6,-19,-15,-16,5,-17,-11,-50,-36,-26,-17,-14,-14,
-13,-12,-13,-13,-13,-17,0,-4,-6,-3,-29,-14,-34,-30,-26,-31,-27,-22,-18,-11,-17,
-17,-20,-20,-20,-12,-15,-8,-16,-12,-24,-14,-16,-19,-49,-19,-49,-49,-49,-49]} 1.
Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. e3 b6 $1 {This is a nice and simple system against this
line with e3... we get good counterplay without any theory... the great move
comes a bit later - ...g6! ...because our bishop is much better placed on g7
in these lines, protecting our king and controlling the center!} 4. b3 (4. Nc3
Bb4 $1 {And we get out of book... with interesting typical Nimzo play, e.g.} 5.
Qb3 (5. Be2 Bxc3) (5. Qc2 Bb7) 5... a5 $1 6. Be2 Bb7 7. O-O O-O 8. a3 $6 Bxc3
9. Qxc3 a4 $132) 4... g6 $1 5. Bb2 Bg7 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O Bb7 $132 {Our next
moves may be ...c5 or ...d5. Usually after White's cxd5 we play ...Nxd5!} 8. d4
d5 $1 {This is good... but it's not the only good move here!} (8... d6 $5 9.
Nc3 Nbd7 10. Qc2 c5 $132 {This is a more fluid setup.}) (8... c5 $1 {Similar
to 8...d6!?} 9. Nc3 (9. Nbd2 d6 10. Rc1 Nbd7 $132) 9... Qe7 10. Rc1 d6 $132) 9.
Nc3 (9. cxd5 Nxd5 $1 {The plan is to go for Grunfeld-like play (in a
comfrotable version).} ({We don't block our bishop with} 9... exd5)) 9... Nbd7
10. Rc1 (10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Rc1 c5 $11 {is the abovemention Grunfeld-type play.}
) 10... c5 11. cxd5 Nxd5 $1 $11 {Let's follow a sample line from my game:} 12.
Nxd5 Bxd5 13. Qd2 Qe7 14. dxc5 Bxb2 15. Qxb2 Nxc5 16. Rfd1 Rad8 17. Ne1 (17. h3
Bxf3 {If this resource is available (based on Bxf3? Nd3!), it's usually good!}
18. gxf3 Rxd1+ (18... a5 $132) 19. Rxd1 Rd8 $132) 17... a5 $11 {The chances
are objectively equal, but the game is not yet as dry to guarantee a drawn
outcome. Little by little, I outplayed my opponent:} 18. Bb5 Qg5 19. Qe2 h5 20.
Bc4 Bb7 21. Rxd8 Rxd8 22. Rd1 h4 23. h3 Qf6 24. Rxd8+ Qxd8 25. Nf3 Qf6 26. Nd4
Ne4 27. Qc2 Nc5 28. Qe2 Kg7 29. a3 e5 30. Nf3 Bxf3 31. Qxf3 Qxf3 32. gxf3 f5
33. b4 axb4 $2 {The endgame is very dangerous for White, but I made w rong
tdecision of trading the pawn in the time-trouble and my opponent managed to
draw.} ({What follows here is a deep analysis without commentary (it is
obviously outside the scope of the course) for the reader's analytical
pleasure:} 33... Nb7 $3 $17 34. Kf1 Nd6 35. Bd3 (35. Bd5 Nb5 36. a4 Nc7 37.
bxa5 bxa5 38. Bc4 Kf6) 35... Kf6 36. Ke1 (36. bxa5 $5 bxa5 37. Ke2 Ke6 38. e4 (
38. Kd2 Kd5 39. Kc3 Kc5) 38... f4 39. Kd2 Kd7 40. Kc3 Nf7 41. Bf1 Ng5 42. Bg2
Kc6 43. Kc4 Ne6 44. Bf1 Nd4 45. Bg2 Nb5 46. a4 Nd6+ 47. Kb3 Kc5 48. Kc3 Nf7 49.
Bf1 Ng5 50. Bg2 Ne6 51. Bf1 Nd4 52. Bg2 Kc6 $3 53. Kc4 (53. Bh1 Ne6 54. Kb3
Nc5+ 55. Ka3 Nd3 56. Kb3 Nxf2 57. Bg2 Nd3 58. Bf1 Nc5+ 59. Ka3 Nd7 60. Bc4 Nf6
61. Bf1 g5 62. Bg2 (62. Be2) 62... g4 63. fxg4 Nh7 64. Kb3 Kc5 65. Kc3 Ng5)
53... Ne6 54. Kb3 Kc5 55. Kc3 Ng5) 36... Ke6 37. Kd2 Kd5 38. Kc3 axb4+ (38...
a4 $19 39. Be2 b5 40. Bf1 (40. Bd3 e4) 40... g5 41. Be2 Nc4 42. Bxc4+ bxc4 43.
b5 Kc5 (43... g4 $19) 44. b6 Kxb6 45. Kxc4 g4) (38... g5 $19 39. Bxf5 (39. Be2
a4 (39... e4) (39... f4 40. e4+ Kc6) 40. Bd1 b5 41. Be2 e4) 39... Nxf5 40. e4+
Ke6 41. exf5+ Kxf5 42. Kc4 Kf4 43. Kb5 axb4 44. axb4 Kxf3 45. Kxb6 g4 46. hxg4
h3) 39. axb4) 34. axb4 Nb7 35. Kf1 Nd6 36. Bd5 g5 37. Ke2 Kf6 38. Bc6 Ke6 39.
e4 f4 40. Kd3 Ke7 41. Ke2 Kd8 42. Ba4 Kc7 43. Ke1 Nc8 (43... g4) 44. Kd2 Kd8
45. Bc6 Ke7 46. Kd3 Nd6 47. Ke2 {1/2 the Nf3-c4-e3 LINE-b6-g6! variation 2017}
1/2-1/2

