1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g4 O-O 5. g5 Ne8 6. h4 {GM Albert David, 9
years after my game wth Morozevich, plays the same line against me... and he
improves White's play with 6.h4!? instead of 6.Rg1... However, Black seems to
have good counterplay with the typical pawn play in the center!} d5 $1 7. Qb3 (
7. d4 {is not much in the spirit of White's idea, it can be countered well with
} Nd6 ({or} 7... dxc4)) 7... c5 8. cxd5 exd5 (8... Nd6 9. g6 $1 hxg6 10. h5 $1
$40 {shows the point of White's improvement. But Black gains compensation in a
different way in the game.}) 9. Qxd5 Nd6 $132 10. Bh3 (10. g6 Be6 11. gxf7+
Bxf7 12. Qg5 Nc6 13. Qxd8 Raxd8 $44 {Black rpeserves compensation in the
endgame.}) (10. e3 $2 {does nothing to stop a series of attack against the
queen.} Be6 11. Qe5 Nc6 12. Qg3 Re8 $17 {Black has gained several tempi and is
closed to winning. There's no real chance of attack:} 13. h5 $2 Nd4 $1 $19)
10... Bxh3 11. Rxh3 Nc6 12. h5 {This position is objectively equal, but it is
asier to play it with Black... on that day though, i wasn't very much in a
fighting spirit!} Ne7 13. Qe5 Nc6 (13... Re8 $1 {was a way to play on:} 14. h6
Nef5 15. Qf4 Qe7 $44) 14. Qd5 (14. Qf4 Qd7 15. Rh1 Qe6 $1 $44 {This is a nice
way for Black to continue with nice compensation for the pawn.}) 14... Ne7 15.
Qe5 Nc6 1/2-1/2

