{[%evp 0,50,19,12,12,21,18,7,20,1,31,31,25,8,20,-1,2,10,40,27,27,-91,44,44,44,
44,48,48,55,48,57,41,56,56,56,15,69,69,69,64,-141,-79,65,-113,-202,-217,-217,
-216,-216,-29977,-29978,-29979,-29980]} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g4 $5
{An interesting but risky system for White... after playing g4 White should
try to castle long... but this will take some time, and Black will strike in
the center with ...d5-c5 etc. ONCE AGAIN NO CONCRETE THEORY IS NEEDED AT ALL!}
O-O $1 5. g5 Ne8 6. Rg1 (6. Qc2 d5 $132 (6... c5 $36 7. a3 Ba5 8. b3 d5 $36 9.
h4 Nc6)) (6. h4 d5 $5 7. Qb3 c5 8. cxd5 exd5 $132) 6... d5 $1 7. Qb3 c5 {
This was a nice over-the-board inspiration, with good counterplay.} (7... Bxc3
8. dxc3 $14 {with the bishop pair for White, would be unsatisfactory.}) 8. cxd5
Nd6 $1 (8... Nc7 9. d6 $1 {would be an unpleasant countergambit to face.} (9.
dxe6 $2 Bxe6 10. Qc2 Nc6 $44 {is excellent for Black.})) 9. Bh3 ({White cannot
afford to allow the accelaration of Black's development by} 9. dxe6 $2 Bxe6 10.
Qc2 Nc6 11. e3 Re8 12. Be2 Rc8 13. d3 b5 $19 {White is busted because of
Black's tremendous activity.}) 9... Na6 10. g6 (10. dxe6 c4 11. Qc2 (11. exf7+
$4 Rxf7 $19) 11... Bxe6 12. Bxe6 fxe6 {Black gets the critically important ...
Rxf3 idea, e.g.} 13. h4 $2 Rxf3 $1 14. exf3 Nc5 $19) 10... c4 11. gxh7+ Kh8 $1
12. Qc2 exd5 13. Bxc8 Rxc8 14. Nxd5 Re8 15. Kf1 Ne4 16. Ne3 Qd7 $44 {The
position is very complex, but it's better to be on the Black side, who has all
the activity. The extra pawns are not important in the foreseeable horizon. It
is easy even for an excellent player like Morozevich to go wrong with White in
a position like this, which he did.} 17. Ng5 $2 (17. d3) ({or} 17. Rg4 {
were better choices.}) 17... Nac5 18. Qxc4 $6 (18. Nf3 {is the lesser evil,
but who would go back now?}) 18... Nxg5 19. Rxg5 Ne4 20. Qb5 $2 (20. Qd5 {
was the last chance to fight, but it's based on an impossible to find computer
idea:} Qc7 21. Rxg7 $3 Kxg7 22. h8=Q+ Kxh8 23. Qh5+ Kg8 24. d3 $17 {and
somehow White fights on.}) 20... Rc6 21. Rf5 (21. Rg2 Rxc1+ 22. Rxc1 Qxb5 $19)
(21. Rd5 Qh3+ 22. Kg1 Rg6+ $19) 21... Nd6 22. Qd3 Rxe3 23. dxe3 Qxf5 24. a3
Qh3+ 25. Kg1 Nf5 {And in the end Greece managed to beat Russia in this
memorable team competition !} 0-1

