{[%evp 0,94,16,16,28,-7,5,-16,28,-3,-7,-7,-8,-12,-19,-26,-32,-34,-21,-14,-7,
-13,3,4,39,13,33,14,32,-17,2,-28,-39,-33,-33,-93,-93,-93,-81,-73,-61,-157,-61,
-175,-222,-205,-138,-185,-220,-254,-231,-308,-229,-505,-270,-256,-234,-281,
-386,-362,-119,-407,-217,-436,-252,-272,-240,-225,-166,-158,-185,-171,-113,
-178,-183,-158,-117,-133,-150,-361,-143,-160,-162,-125,-99,-99,-139,-208,-175,
-388,-419,-419,-189,-640,-843,-29991,-29992]} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4.
Qc2 {The idea of this nice system by White, is usually to stay flexible: first
he will play Qc2 and a3 securing the pair of bishops... and only then he will
decide about his set-up! Black MUST CHOOSE THE SAME SET-UP THAT HE WOULD USE
AGAINST THE 4.Qc2 NIMZO after the moves 1.d4-Nf6 2.c4-e6 3.Nc3-Bb4 4.Qc2
PLEASE NOTE THAT IT IS PLAYED ONLY WITH PLANS, NOT CONCRETE LINES, BY BOTH
SIDES!!} ({In the case of} 4. Qb3 {we don't tak on c3, so easily, but play} a5
$5 (4... Nc6 $5) (4... c5) 5. a3 {This move has an annoying problem for White
now:} ({White can play a variety of moves, like} 5. g3 {We should not memorize
anything by rather play by common sense to achieve a consistent setup, e.g.} d5
({Or the less central} 5... b6 {with a typical line being} 6. Bg2 Bb7 7. O-O
O-O 8. d4 d6 9. Qc2 Bxc3 10. Qxc3 Nbd7 11. b3 Be4)) 5... Bxc3 6. Qxc3 a4 $1 $11
) 4... d6 $5 {Black stays flexible as well... of course, all sorts of moves
are possible here... and memorizing theory would be a total waste of time!} (
4... O-O $5 5. a3 Bxc3 6. Qxc3 d6 (6... b6)) (4... d5 $5) 5. a3 $5 {This is
the main idea... but by no means a forced move!} (5. g3 $5 c5 6. a3 Bxc3 7.
Qxc3 e5 $132) (5. e3 O-O 6. a3 Bxc3 7. Qxc3 e5 $132) 5... Bxc3 6. Qxc3 O-O (
6... a5 $5 7. b3 e5 (7... O-O 8. Bb2 e5 9. g3 c5) 8. Bb2 c5 $5 9. e3 O-O $132)
7. b4 e5 8. Bb2 Re8 {Black has nice counterplay.} 9. e3 Bg4 $5 10. d3 {Giving
Black a chance to take on f3.} ({If} 10. Be2 {we develop the pieces and ...
c6-d5 beocomes on of the main plans:} Nbd7 (10... e4 {is plausible in general
in similar positions, but here it runs into a clever response:} 11. h3 $1 Bh5 (
11... exf3 12. hxg4 fxe2 13. g5 $1 $16) 12. g4 $1 exf3 13. Bxf3 Bg6 14. g5 $14
{With a definite edge for White.}) 11. h3 Bh5 12. d3 c6 13. O-O d5 $132) 10...
Bxf3 $1 11. gxf3 c5 12. Rg1 Nc6 $5 13. Be2 $6 {White plays too softly and
allows Black to take over the game.} (13. bxc5 d5 {was a pawn sacrifice idea
behind 12...Nc6, playable for both sides.} ({But} 13... dxc5 $6 14. f4 $1 $16 {
is problematic for Black.}) 14. O-O-O (14. cxd5 Nxd5 15. Qd2 (15. Qc4 b5 $5 $44
) 15... Rb8 $5 $44 {Preapring ..b6, with full compensation.}) 14... b6 $5 $44 (
14... d4 15. Qc2 Nd7 16. f4 $1 $14)) (13. b5 $2 Nd4 $1 {was another of the
main ideas behind 12...Nc6} 14. Bg2 a6 $17) 13... d5 $1 14. b5 $2 ({There was
a still a sensible path for White:} 14. cxd5 cxb4 15. axb4 Nxd5 16. Qb3 Ndxb4 {
Now White has to play for compensation, which he can try to do with} 17. f4 $15
) (14. bxc5 d4 15. Qd2 Nd7 $17 {An example of knights' domination over bishops.
It's not possible for White to hold onto the pawn advantage at all, e.g.} 16.
exd4 Nxd4 (16... exd4 $5 {might be even stronger.}) 17. Bxd4 exd4 18. Qg5 Qxg5
(18... g6 $17) 19. Rxg5 Rac8 $17 20. Rd5 Nxc5 21. Rxd4 $2 Nb3 $19) 14... d4 15.
Qc2 Ne7 $17 {The bishops are dead, blocked by the pawns now, while the knights
can maneuver without difficulty. The game becomes one sided. Black goes on to
win, admittedly hesitating too much in the process, not immediately clinching
the direct win a few times.} 16. a4 a6 $1 {An important moment. If Black
doesn't play this move here, he will run into a4-a5 when opening the queenside
will not be possible, making the realization of the advantage much harder.} 17.
Rb1 axb5 18. axb5 Qd7 19. Bf1 Ra2 20. Ke2 Ng6 21. Qb3 Rea8 22. Rg3 Qe7 23. Kd2
Qd8 24. Ke2 Nh5 25. Rg1 Qh4 26. Rg4 Qd8 (26... Qxh2 $1 27. Bg2 dxe3 28. fxe3 (
28. Rh1 Nhf4+ 29. Kf1 Ra1+ $19) 28... f5 $19) 27. Rg1 f5 28. Bg2 Qh4 29. Rh1
R8a3 30. Qc2 Rc3 (30... Nhf4+ $1 31. exf4 Nxf4+ 32. Kf1 Nxd3 33. Qe2 Rxb2 34.
Rxb2 Ra1+ $19) 31. Qd2 Rb3 32. Kd1 Qg5 33. Bf1 dxe3 34. fxe3 f4 35. e4 Qd8 36.
Kc2 Rb4 37. Bh3 Nf6 38. Be6+ Kh8 39. Qc3 Qd6 40. Bd5 Nh4 41. Rhf1 Ng2 42. Kc1
Ne3 43. Rf2 Nfxd5 44. exd5 Qg6 45. Re2 h6 46. Kd2 Nxc4+ 47. dxc4 Qxb1 0-1

