-58,-190,-222,-517,-511,-515,-516,-525,-523,-518,-527,-519,-540]} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2.
c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d6 5. a3 Bxc3 6. Qxc3 e5 7. d3 O-O 8. Bg5 $6 {White
plays in an uninspiring fashion, giving up his bishop pair advantage for no
clear gain.} h6 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. g3 ({It's quite obvious, but still worth
pointing out that} 10. e4 $2 {allows the exemplary good knight vs. bad bishop
scenario:} Bg4 11. Be2 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 Nc6 13. O-O Nd4 $17 {With positional
domination approaching a won position.}) 10... Nc6 11. Bg2 Bg4 12. Nd2 ({
There is a concrete prblem with castling:} 12. O-O Bxf3 $1 ({But it's also
possible to preserve the richness of the position with minor pieces and play
something like} 12... a5 $5 {, also with promising chances.}) 13. Bxf3 Nd4 14.
Kg2 Nxf3 15. exf3 $15 {Black is slightly better thanks to the structural edge,
at least in practice. The uncaring computer claims it's still equal, but what
matters in a practical game is that Black has something to build his winning
chances upon, contrary to White.}) 12... Nd4 13. f3 Bh5 $15 {Black gets the
initiative, but White holds his own over the next several moves, before a
blunder costs him the game.} 14. Kf2 g5 15. Ne4 Qg7 16. e3 Ne6 17. g4 Bg6 18.
Ng3 f5 19. gxf5 Bxf5 20. Nxf5 Rxf5 21. Bh3 $2 {A fatal miscalculation.} g4 22.
Bxg4 Qxg4 23. Rag1 Rxf3+ 24. Ke1 Rxe3+ 25. Kd2 Re2+ 26. Kc1 Rg2 {White
probably missed from afar that the rook is able to block the g-file after
delivering a few checks.} 0-1

