3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3 {Against this move, Black achieves a good game by the simple
central strategy: castling followed by ...d5.} O-O 5. Bg2 d5 6. cxd5 (6. O-O
dxc4 7. a3 Bd6 8. Qa4 e5 {Expanding in the centre, the best method in such
positions.} 9. Qxc4 Nc6 $11 {The light-squared bishop is open and ready to
move out. White can liquidate in the centre by means of 10.d4, but that only
brings him equality.}) 6... exd5 7. d4 {Black has a very satisfactory position
similar to the Carlsbad line of my Romanishin System course.} Re8 ({The game
move can be postopned in favour of the ..c6, ...Bd6 setup, when Black's
chances are somwhat better:} 7... c6 8. O-O Bd6 9. Bg5 (9. b3 Bf5 10. Bb2 Nbd7
$15) 9... Nbd7 10. e4 dxe4 11. Nxe4 Be7 12. Nxf6+ Nxf6 $15) 8. Bg5 h6 9. Bxf6
Qxf6 10. O-O c6 11. Ne5 Bd6 12. f4 Bf5 13. Qb3 Qe7 14. Rae1 Na6 15. a3 Be6 16.
Qc2 f6 17. Ng6 Qf7 $2 {White gains some really strong play after this.} (17...
Qd7 $11) 18. f5 Bd7 19. e4 dxe4 20. Nxe4 Bc7 21. g4 Rad8 22. Rd1 Bc8 23. Rfe1
Bb8 24. Bf1 Nc7 25. Bc4 Nd5 26. Qf2 Kh7 27. Re2 a6 28. Rde1 Ba7 29. Kh1 b5 30.
Ba2 c5 31. dxc5 Bb7 32. Kg1 b4 33. axb4 Qd7 34. Rd2 Qc6 35. Qf3 $4 {White has
been winning or close to winning the whole time, but this and another blunder
finally turn the result around.} (35. g5 $1 fxg5 36. Qf3 $1 $18 {with the
lethal Nxg5+ threat wins.}) 35... Nxb4 36. Rxd8 Bxc5+ 37. Kg2 Rxd8 38. Bb1 Nd5
$2 (38... Qb5 $1 $19) 39. g5 fxg5 40. Nxg5+ Kg8 41. Ne6 $4 (41. Ne4 $11) 41...
Nf4+ 0-1

