{This course offers a repertoire for Black in the Romanishin System, i.e.} 1.
Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 a6 $5 {Black carries out an unusual idea of a flank
pawn break early on in the opening, with a clear strategical goal of
exchanging a flank pawn for a more central pawn early on in the game and
establish a strong centre later. Obviously, ...b5 also opens a possibility of
an extended fianchetto that we will often use to neutralize the white
g2-bishop. We will consider all the relevant variations, the critical option
being} 4. Bg2 ({After} 4. Nc3 {we will transfer the game to a Carlsbad-type
structure, where we want to benefit from White's kingside fianchetto - the
bishop will not be effective on g2, hitting the rock-solid d5-point:} d5 5.
cxd5 exd5 6. d4 Bd6) 4... b5 5. b3 $1 {, when White doesn't concede a
strategically unfavourable exchange.} *

