{[%evp 0,30,16,28,27,-16,-17,-4,11,-2,18,3,9,17,37,23,13,20,28,37,30,6,17,-7,
-7,-26,-26,-34,-19,-48,-39,-49,-48]} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 a6 $5 4. Bg2 (4.
Nc3 $5 {SEE GAME SESSION!! THIS is not a very dangerous system... it is quite
possible that we will reach a typical Crlsbad position in the end.} d5 $1 5.
cxd5 (5. d4 dxc4 6. Bg2 (6. Qa4+ $4 b5 7. Nxb5 Bd7 $19) 6... b5 7. Ne5 (7. O-O
$2 Bb7 $15 {way too easy for black now...pawn up and fast development!} 8. a4
b4 9. Nb1 c5) 7... Ra7 8. Bc6+ $5 (8. O-O Bb7 $15) 8... Bd7 9. Bg2 c5 $132 (
9... Bc8 $1)) 5... exd5 6. d4 (6. Bg2 Be7 $1 (6... Bd6 $5 7. O-O O-O 8. d3 $1 (
8. d4 $6 c6) 8... h6 9. e4 dxe4 10. dxe4 Nc6 $132 11. Re1 $14) 7. O-O O-O 8. d4
(8. d3 d4 $1 9. Ne4 Nxe4 10. dxe4 c5 $132) 8... c6 $132) 6... Bd6 $1 7. Bg2 O-O
8. O-O c6 9. Bf4 (9. Bg5 $6 Nbd7 10. e4 dxe4 11. Nxe4 Be7 $15) 9... Bxf4 $1 10.
gxf4 Ne8 $3 $15 11. e3 Nd6 12. Rc1 Bf5 13. Ne5 Nd7 14. b3 Re8 15. Re1 Nf8 $17 (
15... f6)) 4... b5 5. b3 $1 {This is the best move for White, as it seems!} (5.
d4 $6 bxc4 6. Ne5 d5 7. Nxc4 c5 $132 {Black has great potential for a better
game with more pawns in the centre:} 8. O-O Nc6 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. b3 O-O 11. Bb2
Bb7 $15) (5. Ne5 Ra7 $1 {And next is ...Bb7 with a tempo and a good position!}
6. Nc3 Bb7 $1 7. Bxb7 Rxb7 8. d3 d6 9. Nf3 c5 10. O-O Be7 $15) (5. Nd4 $6 c6 6.
cxb5 axb5 7. Nxb5 $6 cxb5 $1 8. Bxa8 d5 {generally ..the plan is Qa5...and
slowly trap the bishop!} 9. a4 (9. O-O Qa5 10. Qc2 Bd7 11. Bb7 Qb6 12. Bc8 Bc6
13. d3 Bd6 14. Be3 Qc7 15. Bxe6 fxe6 $15) 9... Qa5 10. Qc2 Bd7 11. Bb7 Bb4 $1 (
11... bxa4 12. Bc8 (12. Nc3 Qa7 (12... Qc7)) 12... Bc6 13. O-O Bd6 14. Nc3 O-O
15. Bxe6 fxe6 16. Nxa4 e5) 12. O-O O-O 13. d3 Qb6 14. Ba8 bxa4 15. Nc3 Qa6 $17)
(5. O-O bxc4 $1 {We take the pawn... just so that we will create a strong
center with ...d5-c5, not in order to try and keep the pawn!} (5... Bb7 $5 6.
d3 c5 7. Bg5 Be7 8. e4 O-O 9. e5 Ne8 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 $11) 6. Ne5 d5 7. Nxc4 c5 $1
8. Nc3 Be7 9. d3 O-O 10. Bf4 (10. Bd2 Nc6 $15) 10... Nc6 $132 {Black's centre
is impressive, contrary to White's.}) (5. d3 $5 Bb7 6. O-O bxc4 $5 7. dxc4 Be7
(7... c5) 8. Nc3 O-O $132 9. b3 (9. Qc2 d6 10. e4 {This kind of expansion can
easily backfire:} c5 11. Rd1 Qc7 12. b3 Nc6 $15 {The e4-advance has weakened
the d4-square. White would prefer the pawn on e3. Even ...e5 followed by ...
Nd4 may come at some point, posing White problems.}) 9... d6 10. Bb2 c5 11. Qc2
Nc6 $132) 5... Bb7 $5 (5... c5 $5 {is a viable alternative, but we focus on
the main recommndation in this course.} 6. Nc3 Qb6 7. e4 Bb7 8. e5 Ne4) 6. Nc3
$1 (6. Bb2 $6 {this..is already very slow...and now we get a great game...by
castling safely...and having our bishop nicely developed on b7...and we even
got b7-b5 in...for nice counterplay on the queenside! (PAP)} c5 $1 7. Nc3 Qb6 (
7... bxc4 $5 8. bxc4 Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Rb1 d6 11. Ba1 Bc6 12. d3 Qc7 13. e4
Nbd7 $132) 8. O-O Be7 9. d3 (9. Re1 O-O 10. e4 d6 11. d4 cxd4 12. Nxd4 (12.
Qxd4 $6 Qxd4 13. Nxd4 bxc4 14. bxc4 Nbd7 $15 15. e5 $2 Bxg2 16. exf6 Bxf6 17.
Kxg2 Bxd4) 12... Nc6 13. Nxc6 Qxc6 $132) 9... O-O 10. e4 $6 (10. e3 d6 11. Qe2
Nc6 (11... Nbd7 12. Rab1 Rab8 $132)) 10... d6 $15 11. Ne1 Nc6 12. f4 Nd7 $15) (
6. O-O $1 c5 $1 {so that we will be on time to defend with Qb6! after Nc3} 7.
Nc3 Qb6 $1 8. d4 $5 {we are fine here...as long as we know what to do!} (8. d3
Be7 9. e4 O-O 10. Re1 d6) (8. Re1 Be7 9. e4 O-O $1 (9... d6 $2 10. d4 cxd4 11.
Nxd4 $18 b4 12. Nd5 exd5 13. exd5 $18 {This is a positional...nightmare ! ..
black can hardly move...and in fact white can take his time to win slowly but
surely!}) 10. e5 Ne8 $132 11. d4 (11. Bb2 Nc6 12. Rb1 f6 13. exf6 Nxf6 $132)
11... cxd4 12. Qxd4 Bc5 $132) 8... cxd4 9. Qxd4 $1 (9. Nxd4 $2 Bxg2 10. Kxg2
Nc6 $1 $15) 9... Qxd4 10. Nxd4 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 Nc6 (11... bxc4 12. bxc4 d6 $1 13.
Ba3 Nbd7 14. Na4 $5 (14. Rfc1 Rc8 15. Nd1 Be7 $132 16. Rab1 Rc7 $1 17. f3 O-O)
14... Rc8 15. Rfc1 Be7 16. Rab1 Rc7 $132) 12. Nxc6 dxc6 $132) (6. Na3 b4 7. Nc2
c5 $132 {This is an exception from the rule of not playing ...b4 and ...c5 at
the same time. The reason why this is good now is that the white knight cannot
reach a4 and is more passive on c2.}) 6... Bb4 $1 {An effective resource that
keeps the balance in the opening.} (6... b4 7. Na4 c5 $2 {Remember that we
want to avoid this structure. We can play ...c5 or ...b4 in various lines, but
it's generally not good to combine both moves. Let's see why:} 8. Bb2 Be7 9.
O-O O-O 10. d4 cxd4 11. Nxd4 Bxg2 12. Kxg2 {The knight on a4 is not out of
play at all in such position, in fact it is quite powerful. Notice that the
knight gains scope after the black pawn leaves c7, making b6 weaker.} Qc7 (
12... Nc6 13. Nxc6 dxc6 14. Qxd8 Rfxd8 15. Bxf6 (15. Rfd1 $14) 15... Bxf6 16.
Rad1 $14 {A classical endgame with an upper hand for White. The knight
threatens a highly problematic penetration to b6 or c5.}) 13. e3 Nc6 14. Nxc6
Qxc6+ 15. Qf3 Qxf3+ 16. Kxf3 $14 {Again the endgame is clearly in White's
favour and Black wishes his pawn was not stuck on b4.}) (6... bxc4 7. bxc4) 7.
Bb2 (7. cxb5 Bxc3 8. dxc3 axb5 9. O-O (9. Qd3 Bc6 10. O-O O-O $132) 9... Be4 $5
$132) 7... bxc4 $5 {Now that White has blocked the b-file with Bb2, it is
natural and good to take on c4.} (7... d6 $1 {Another very good and simple
move!} 8. O-O (8. cxb5 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 axb5 10. O-O Nbd7 $132) 8... Nbd7 9. Qc2
bxc4 (9... O-O 10. a3 Bxc3 11. Qxc3 c5 $132) 10. bxc4 c5 $132) (7... O-O $5) 8.
bxc4 c5 9. O-O O-O 10. Rb1 (10. d4 cxd4 11. Na4 Be4 $1 {It's a nice idea to
plonk the bishop on e4 before developing the knight to c6, in order not to
allow a comfortable Nxd4 move with a pin.} 12. Bxd4 Nc6 13. Bb6 Qb8 $132) 10...
d6 11. d3 Nbd7 12. Ba1 Rb8 13. Qc2 Qc7 $132 {Black has achieved a safe and
equal game, with possibilities of playing in a few different ways, as the
following sample line shows:} 14. Nh4 Bxg2 15. Nxg2 d5 $5 $132 {Building a
centre.} (15... Bxc3 $5 {Another full-fledged possibility.} 16. Bxc3 Qc6 $132 {
In this relatively closed position Black's knights are not worse than White's
knight and bishop.}) *

