{[%evp 0,67,61,58,18,-9,4,-27,11,12,46,9,23,23,37,44,48,40,33,49,38,-11,-5,-17,
21,-7,-11,-26,-26,-29,-29,-29,-24,-40,-33,-40,-29,-51,-52,-47,-50,-72,-72,-96,
29,-40,-34,-38,-39,-113,-116,-139,-87,-97,-94,-270,-219,-233,-126,-147,-124,
-108,-96,-135,-136,-131,-127,-150,-106,-110]} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 a6 4.
Bg2 b5 5. b3 ({Let's consider a sample line:} 5. cxb5 axb5 6. O-O Bb7 7. b3 Be7
8. Bb2 c5 {Fighting for space in the centre.} 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Bxg2 {
A good rule is to take on g2, and not play ...Qb6. We want to see the white
king on g2, because a possible check on the long diagonal can be connected
with a beneficial tactical opportunity at some moment later in the game.} 11.
Kxg2 Qb6 12. Nd2 Nc6 13. N2f3 (13. Nxc6 Qxc6+) 13... b4 $11 {Another good
resource, fixing the queenside structure. Black has a comfortable game.}) 5...
Bb7 6. Nc3 Bb4 7. O-O {A very strategically risky choice that Black takes
advantage of.} Bxc3 8. dxc3 bxc4 9. bxc4 O-O {The problem in this type of
position for White is that his bishop pair advantage is hardly felt, because
his light-squared bishop is fully neutralized by its black counterpart. The
plan of Bh3, Nd2, f3-e4, which is plausible in some related positions, is only
counterproductive in the specific structure we have now.} 10. Ba3 Re8 11. Qb3
Qc8 (11... Be4 {is another typical move.}) 12. Rab1 Be4 13. Ne5 $2 {It's a
step in the wrong direction to trade the bishops.} Bxg2 14. Kxg2 d6 15. Nd3 c5
$1 $17 {White's minor pieces are perfectly restricted and the control over the
b-file alone doesn't give him much. The weakness on c4 remains.} 16. Rfd1 Qc6+
17. f3 Nbd7 18. Qb7 Qa4 19. Qb3 Qa5 20. Nb2 Ne5 21. Na4 h5 $2 {A bit reckless.}
(21... Qc7 $19 {was the correct path to winning the game.}) 22. Rxd6 Rab8 23.
Nb6 Ned7 24. Bb4 $2 {Just losing a piece.} (24. Bc1 $1 $11 {was still ok.})
24... cxb4 25. Nxd7 Nxd7 26. cxb4 Qc7 27. Qd3 Ne5 28. Qd4 Red8 29. c5 f6 30.
Rd1 Rxd6 31. Qxd6 Qxd6 32. Rxd6 Rxb4 33. Rxe6 Rc4 34. Rxa6 0-1

