4. Bg2 b5 5. b3 Bb7 6. Nc3 Bb4 7. Bb2 d6 8. O-O (8. cxb5 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 axb5 10.
O-O Nbd7 11. Nd4 {A good maneuver to counter such a direct attempt is} Bxg2 12.
Kxg2 Qb8 $1 {, when it's easy for White to become worse if he's not careful, e.
g.} 13. e3 $6 c5 $1 14. Nf3 b4 $1 $17 {With great light squares and a fixed
weakness on a2.}) 8... O-O 9. Qc2 bxc4 10. bxc4 Nbd7 11. Rab1 c5 12. a3 Ba5
$132 ({Exchange of the bishops is also reasonable, because it increase the
influence of our remaining bishop:} 12... Bxc3 13. Bxc3 Rb8 $132) 13. d3 Re8
14. e4 Rb8 15. h3 Ba8 {Clearing up the b-file for the rook.} 16. Nh4 Ne5 $1 {
A good reaction to White's f2-f4 plan. The knight heads towards d4.} 17. f4 Nc6
18. Ne2 Nd7 19. Ba1 Rxb1 20. Rxb1 Qc7 21. g4 Bb6 22. Nf3 Nd4 $1 {A good move
that offers White a chance to go wrong.} 23. Nexd4 cxd4 24. Qf2 $2 (24. Bxd4 {
was obligatory.} Bxd4+ 25. Nxd4 Qc5 26. Qf2 Qxa3 $15 {It's not pleasant for
White, but it's not nearly as bad as the position White gets in the game.})
24... e5 $1 $19 {The bishop on a1 becomes a dead piece, diametrically changing
the nature of the game in Black's favour. Black's slow by steady invasion on
the queenside becomes inevitable. Black goes on to win easily.} 25. f5 Bc5 26.
Qa2 Qa5 27. Bb2 Rb8 28. Bc1 Rxb1 29. Qxb1 Bxa3 30. Bxa3 Qxa3 31. f6 g6 32. g5
Bc6 33. h4 a5 34. Bh3 Qb4 35. Qf1 a4 36. h5 a3 37. hxg6 hxg6 38. Be6 a2 39. Qh3
a1=Q+ 40. Kg2 Nf8 41. Bxf7+ Kxf7 42. Qh8 Ke8 43. f7+ Kxf7 0-1

