{A typical example with slow play by White in the Romanishin variation...
Black doesn't have the slightest problem!} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 a6 4. Bg2
b5 5. b3 c5 6. O-O Bb7 7. Bb2 Be7 8. d3 O-O 9. e4 d6 10. e5 dxe5 11. Nxe5 Bxg2
12. Kxg2 Nfd7 $3 $15 {A very strong idea worth remembering. The knight from b8
keeps controlling c6 while the kingside knight is used for exchange.} (12...
Qc7 {This path is not bad, but less effective.} 13. Nd2 Nbd7 (13... Nfd7 14.
Nxd7 Qxd7 $11) 14. Nxd7 Qxd7 $11) (12... Nbd7 $6 13. Nc6 $14 {is not great, of
course.}) 13. Qf3 (13. Nxd7 Qxd7 {We take with the queen, because the best
place for the knight is c6.} 14. Qg4 {We have to consider this attacking move,
but it's not a big problem.} f6 (14... g6 {Also good.}) 15. Re1 e5 16. Qxd7
Nxd7) 13... Ra7 $1 $15 (13... Nxe5 $1 $15 {was possible, in view of} 14. Qxa8
$2 Nxd3 15. Bc3 b4 $19) 14. Na3 $6 (14. Nxd7 Rxd7 $17 {With pressure against
d3 and the upper hand.}) (14. Nd2 $1 $15 {was a lesser evil.}) 14... Bf6 $1 {
Starting favourable exchanges.} 15. Nxd7 Bxb2 16. Nxf8 Bxa3 17. Nxe6 fxe6 18.
Rae1 Qd6 $17 {White has insufficient compensation for the two minor pieces and
goes on to lose.} 19. Qe4 Re7 20. f4 Qc6 21. Kh3 Qxe4 22. Rxe4 Nc6 23. f5 e5
24. g4 Rd7 25. Rf3 h6 26. Kg2 Kf7 27. h4 Kf6 28. Kh3 Rd4 29. Re1 Nb4 30. g5+
hxg5 31. hxg5+ Kxg5 32. Rxe5 Rxd3 33. f6+ Kg6 34. Rg5+ Kxg5 35. fxg7 Rxf3+ 36.
