112,106,163,171,199,80,191,246,281,207,327,294,413,-29991,-29992,-29993,-29994,
-29995,-29996,-29997,-29998,-29999,-30000] A good example by Black against
slow play from White} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 a6 4. Bg2 b5 5. b3 Bb7 6. O-O
c5 7. Bb2 Be7 8. d3 ({It is usually more promising for White to go for the
more energetic quick e2-e4 advance:} 8. Nc3 Qb6 9. Re1 (9. d3 O-O 10. e4 d6)
9... O-O 10. e4 d6 {Logical when we have already castled there is no need to
allow e5.} 11. d4 cxd4 12. Nxd4 Nc6 13. cxb5 Nxd4 14. Na4 Qxb5 15. Qxd4 Rfd8
$132) 8... O-O 9. Nbd2 Qb6 10. Qc2 d6 11. Rac1 Nc6 12. e3 Nd7 13. Rfd1 Bf6 14.
Bxf6 Nxf6 15. a3 Rac8 16. Rb1 Rfd8 17. h3 h6 18. Qc3 d5 $15 {The game has
proceeded very logicaly until here. Black got his pieces on good squares and
gains space in the centre with the last move. The position is attractive for
Black.} 19. d4 $2 b4 $2 {There was a simple win for Black, missed by both
sides, probably because it was a blitz game. Later Black misplays the position
but eventually wins after White blunders.} (19... cxd4 20. exd4 dxc4 21. bxc4
Nxd4 $19) 20. axb4 cxb4 21. Qa1 a5 22. c5 Qc7 23. Qb2 Ba6 24. Rbc1 Na7 25. Ne5
