1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 a6 4. Bg2 b5 5. Ne5 $6 {Another harmless move by
White... just remember to play ...Ra7 and then ...Bb7! with tempo!} Ra7 6. O-O
(6. Nc3 Bb7 $1) 6... Bb7 {The most natural. There are other good options as
well.} (6... bxc4 7. Nxc4 d5 $11) (6... d6 7. Nc6 (7. Nf3 c5 $11) (7. Bc6+ $2
Ke7 8. b3 b4 $1 $19 {The Ba3 idea is blocked and the whole attempt by White
fails.} (8... dxe5 $2 9. Ba3+ $18)) 7... Nxc6 8. Bxc6+ Bd7 $11) 7. cxb5 axb5 8.
Nc3 Bxg2 9. Kxg2 b4 10. Nb5 Rb7 11. a4 ({White could have played} 11. Nd4 {
But the game would have been very promising for Black all the same, e.g.} c5
12. Nc2 d6 13. Nf3 Be7 14. d3 ({White should rather play more energetically
with} 14. d4 $15 {But a lot of players will in fact chose the setup with d3.})
14... O-O 15. b3 Nc6 $17 {A position like this is not equal at all. The pawn
is fixed as a long term-weakness on a2 and Black also has better control of
the centre.}) 11... bxa3 12. Nxa3 Be7 13. Qc2 O-O 14. Nac4 c5 15. Ra8 d6 16.
Na5 Rb5 17. Nec6 Qc7 18. Nxe7+ Qxe7 $15 {Black is slightly better. White makes
a series of tactical blunders and loses.} 19. Qc4 $2 Rb4 20. Qc3 Qc7 21. Nc4 $2
Qb7+ 22. Qf3 Qxf3+ 23. Kxf3 Rxc4 24. d3 Rb4 25. Bd2 Rxb2 26. Be3 Nc6 27. Ra6
Ne5+ 28. Kg2 Rd8 29. Rfa1 h6 30. Kf1 Neg4 0-1

