{White played very passively in the Carlsbad structure... and Black soon took
over... it is instructive to see what to do in a similar case with Black} 1. c4
Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 a6 4. Nc3 d5 (4... b5 5. cxb5 axb5 6. Nxb5 Ba6 7. Nc3 d5 8.
Bg2 c5 9. O-O Be7 10. d3 O-O 11. Re1 Nc6 12. b3) 5. cxd5 (5. Bg2 $6 {is
clearly not a good approach in view of} d4 6. Nb1 c5 $15) 5... exd5 6. d4 c6 7.
Bg2 Be7 {Carlsbad with the white bishop stuck on g2 like here is very good for
Black. There is no clear plan for White, the bishop doesn't support a minority
attack compared to a classical Carlsbad.} 8. O-O O-O 9. Qc2 Nbd7 10. b3 $6 Re8
11. Bb2 Bd6 $15 {Black needs to firmly control the e5-square.} 12. Rad1 Qe7 $3
{Black makes preparations for ...Ne4 to establish a grip over the centre.} (
12... Nf8 13. Ne5 $1) 13. Nd2 ({In the case of} 13. Nh4 {we don't mind giving
up a bishop for a knight.} Nf8 (13... g6) 14. Nf5 Bxf5 15. Qxf5 $15 {Our
remaining bishop is very strong here.}) (13. e3 Ne4 (13... Nf8 $6 14. Ne5 $1 {
is something to avoid.}) 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Nd2 Nf6 16. Nc4 Bf5 {This is the
plan, with an excellent position. We don't mind Nxd6:} 17. Nxd6 Qxd6 $17 {
The light-squared domination will bring Black obvious benefits.}) 13... Nf8 (
13... Bb4 $5 {was worth considering.}) 14. e4 dxe4 15. Ndxe4 Nxe4 16. Bxe4 Bg4
17. f3 $6 {White goes a bit wrong with this unnecessary weakening.} Bh3 18.
Rfe1 Qg5 19. Bc1 Qa5 20. Bd2 Qc7 21. Ne2 Ng6 22. Kh1 Re7 23. Bg5 f6 24. Bxg6 $2
{White makes a terrible choice of giving up his bishop and goes on to lose.}
hxg6 $17 25. Bf4 Rae8 26. Qd2 g5 27. Bxd6 Qxd6 28. Ng1 Be6 29. Re3 g4 30. Rde1
gxf3 31. Nxf3 Bg4 32. Nh4 Rxe3 33. Rxe3 Rd8 34. Ng2 Kf8 35. Nf4 Qxd4 36. Ng6+
Kf7 37. Nh8+ Kg8 38. Re8+ Kh7 39. Qxd4 Rxd4 40. Nf7 Rd1+ 41. Kg2 Rd2+ 0-1

