{A very good game with typical Carlsbad play!} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 a6 4.
Nc3 d5 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg2 Bd6 7. O-O (7. d4 c6) 7... O-O 8. d4 (8. d3 h6 {
Stopping Bg5 is the most straightforward choice. Black doesn't need to fear
e2-e4.} 9. e4 dxe4 10. dxe4 Nc6 $132) 8... Nbd7 9. Bf4 Bxf4 10. gxf4 {A
promising position for Black, with various effective ways to play.} Nb6 ({
Another very good maneuver worth knowing is ...Ne8-d6, possible after the
preliminary ...c6.} 10... c6 11. Ne5 Ne8 $15 {Things can easily turn from
slight worse to much worse for White, e.g.} 12. Rc1 (12. Nxd7 Bxd7 13. Rc1 Nd6
$17 {This is even worse for White than it looks.}) 12... Nd6 13. e3 Re8 14. Qc2
Nf8 $17 {The knight will be kicked out of e5 with ...f6, ...Bf5 will come with
a tempo, etc.}) ({Black can also plan to put the knight on f8 starting with} 
10... Re8 $15) 11. Ne5 Bf5 12. Rc1 (12. Nd3 {Black can seriously consider
giving up his bishop in a position like this, with the following strategical
dream scenario:} Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Nc4 14. b3 Nd6 15. e3 c6 16. Rfd1 Nfe4 17. Rac1
Nxc3 18. Qxc3 f5 $17 {The bishop is dead, an attack is ready with ...Rf6-h6, ..
.Qh4.}) 12... Ne4 13. e3 Nxc3 14. Rxc3 c6 15. Kh1 f6 16. Nf3 Nc4 (16... Bg4 $1
{was a better choice here, trying to achieve the desired configuration shown
in the last comment.}) 17. Nh4 Nd6 18. Nxf5 Nxf5 19. Bh3 Nd6 20. f5 $6 {
Unfortunately for White, this only creates a hook that Black will exploit.} Qe7
21. f3 Kh8 22. Re1 Rae8 23. Qd3 Qf7 24. Bg4 g6 $3 {Instead of trying to target
the f5-pawn in the long run, Black exchanges it to target White tactically.} (
24... g5 $5) 25. fxg6 (25. Rc2 gxf5 26. Bxf5 Qh5 27. Bg4 Qh4 $19 {The coming ..
.f5 move heralds White's downfall.}) 25... Qxg6 (25... hxg6 $17 {was at least
as good.}) 26. Qxg6 hxg6 $17 {White is in terrible shape in the endgame with
the chronic weakness on e3 and a bad bishop.} 27. Bh3 Rf7 28. Kg1 Rfe7 29. b3
f5 30. f4 Ne4 31. Rc2 Kg7 32. Bg2 Kf6 $2 {This move allows White serious
holding chances.} (32... Nf6 $1 33. Rce2 Ng4 34. Bf3 Kf6 $1 $19 {was clearly
winning. The exchange on g4 doesn't help, as the black king gains the ideal
f5-square then.}) 33. Bxe4 Rxe4 34. Rce2 $2 {Too passive.} (34. Kf2 $17 {
was much more tenacious and gave White solid defensive chances.}) 34... g5 $1 {
Black is in complete control again and he goes on to win convincingly.} 35.
fxg5+ Kxg5 36. Rg2+ Kf6 37. Rge2 a5 38. Kf2 f4 39. Kf3 Kf5 40. h3 fxe3 41. Rxe3
Rf4+ 42. Kg3 (42. Ke2 Rxe3+ 43. Kxe3 Re4+) 42... Rxe3+ 43. Rxe3 Rxd4 44. Re7
Rd3+ 45. Kh4 b5 46. Ra7 a4 47. bxa4 Rd4+ 48. Kg3 Rxa4 49. Rc7 Ra3+ 50. Kh4 Rc3
0-1

