1. c4 {When dealing with the English, Black should be aware of the many
possible transpostions. We don't want to get "move-ordered" into positions
which are not part of our opening preparation. Whenever possible, our
suggested repertoire will be in the spirit of Nimzo-Indian Defence or
Bogo-Indian Defence. But first, let's take a quick look at Black's and White's
options in general.} e5 {This is our choice - the Reversed Sicilian. By
playing 1...e5 we determine the opening and limit White's options. Moreover,
it offers great flexibility: within the next few moves, Black can always
choose between 2-3 playable continuations.} ({If Black hopes to reach a
Nimzo-Indian with the moves} 1... Nf6 2. Nc3 e6 {he might face} 3. e4 {- the
Mikenas Attack.}) ({The Symmetrical Variation} 1... c5 {is another possible
way of meeting the English. However, compared to 1...e5, White has many
possible ways to play and we would have to know a lot of theory.}) (1... e6 {
might be an alternative solution to NImzo-players:} 2. Nc3 (2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3
Bb4 {(= one of the lines in the suggested repertoire against 1.Nf3)}) ({
White can go for} 2. g3 {with a possible transposition to the Catalan.If that
doen't bother Black, then 1...e6 can be a good choice.}) 2... Bb4 $5 {with
play in the spirit of the Nimzo.}) 2. Nc3 ({The other main line} 2. g3 {
will be examined in Part 2.}) 2... Bb4 {This is only the third most popular
move, but still a very decent one! In many lines, we get positions in the
spirit of the Nimzo-Indian. Now there are three possible scenarios: 1) If
White lets us, we take on c3 and double his pawns. This is often combined with
...f5. 2) If White avoids the doubled pawns with Qc2 and follows it up with a3,
we take on c3 and (if he takes back with the queen) go for ...d5. We get a
very active position resembling a reversed Open Sicilian, where White has lost
some time moving his queen. 3) If White plays 3.Nd5, we support our bishop
with 3...a5 (3...Bc5 and 3...Be7 are fully-fledged alternatives).  A (very)
short overview of Black's other options (you can find a more extensive
overview at https://www.modern-chess.com/chess-openings/english-opening):} ({
The main continuation is} 2... Nf6 {For example} 3. Nf3 ({After} 3. g3 {
Black again has a choice betwenn} d5 (3... Bb4 {(Reversed Rossolimo)}) 4. cxd5
Nxd5 {(Reversed Dragon)}) 3... Nc6 (3... e4 $5 4. Ng5 c6 $5 {is a trendy
gambit line.}) 4. g3 ({Against} 4. e3 {,} Bb4 {is the most dependable
continuation.} (4... d5 {is seen less often, as after} 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bb5 {
White has good chances for a small opening advantage.})) 4... d5 (4... Bb4 {
- a reversed Rossolimo Sicilian.}) 5. cxd5 Nxd5 {The Reversed Dragon is one of
the main tabias of the English Opening.}) (2... Nc6 {- Black's second most
popular move. He will continue with ...g6, analogous to the Reversed Closed
Sicilian, or the more aggressive ...f5.} 3. Nf3 (3. g3 g6 {leads to the
Reversed Closed Sicilian.} (3... f5 $5 {is also playable.})) 3... f5 {A very
aggressive and interesting option!} (3... g6 4. d4 {is thought to give White a
small advantage.})) *

