1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 $5 {This is slightly more common than 2.g3, but in my opinion
2.g3 is better!} (2. d3 Nf6 3. e3 Bb4+ $5 {Playing the Sicilian with a tempo
less, we should better play a quiet system with ...Bb4+ (3.Bb5+ in the
Sicilian), rather than 3...d5 leading to a reversed Open Sicilian!} (3... d5 4.
cxd5 Nxd5) 4. Bd2 Bxd2+ 5. Nxd2 O-O 6. Ngf3 Re8) (2. a3 Nf6 3. d3 c6 {Playing
a c3-Sicilian leads to a comfortable game, as the extra tempo a3 is not very
useful for White in this case.} ({We can also go for a Najdorf with colours
reversed:} 3... d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. e4 Nf6 $11 {Since we are a tempo
down, we should choose a quiet system with short castling.})) 2... Bb4 $1 {
A very interesting line, popularised by Vishy Anand in recent years! If Black
is given the chance, he will double White's pawns by taking on c3 and follow
up with ...d6 and ...f5 (either directly or after ...Ne7)!  SOS !! WE DON'T
NEED TO MEMORIZE ANYTHING IN THE LINES WITH THE DOUBLED c- PAWNS !! JUST GO
THROUGH THE LINES A FEW TIMES AND GET A FEELING FOR THE TYPICAL PLANS! In the
best line for White, 3.Nd5!, we only need to memorise very few things. In fact,
we get nice play without having to know much theory!} 3. Nd5 $1 (3. e3 $2 {
Of all the moves that allow ...Bxc3, this is the worst, because it closes the
diagonal of the c1-bishop as well!} Bxc3 4. bxc3 {In general, the play is
quite similar no matter if White takes back with the b- or the d-pawn on c3.} (
4. dxc3 d6 $11) 4... d6 5. d4 (5. d3 f5 $1 (5... Nf6 $2 6. e4 $11) 6. Nf3 Nf6
7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O c5 $15 (8... Nbd7 $15) (8... Nc6 $15) 9. d4 Qe7 10. Ba3 (10.
Qc2 Nc6 11. d5 Nd8 12. Nd2 Nf7 13. e4 f4 14. f3 g5 $19) 10... b6 11. Nd2 Nc6
12. Bf3 Bd7 (12... e4 $5) 13. e4 f4 14. dxc5 dxc5 15. Re1 g5 $19) 5... c5 $1 6.
dxe5 ({After} 6. d5 {we play} f5 $1 {Compared to the Nimzo-Indian, our f-pawn
can advance immediately.} {For example} 7. Qh5+ g6 8. Qd1 Nf6 {White has
provoked the weakening or our dark squares, but he cannot exploit it since his
c1-bishop is shut in by the e3-pawn.} 9. f3 O-O $17 ({Even the impressive} 9...
Kd7 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Yd7c7] is playable.})) (6. Nf3 e4 (6... Nc6 {was also
possible. For instance,} 7. Bd3 (7. dxc5 dxc5 8. Qd5 $2 Qa5 $1 $17 9. Bd2 Nf6
10. Qd6 Bf5 $17 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Ya8d8]}) 7... f5 8. e4 Nf6 $1 {Using a small
tactic to develop the pieces in the best way.} 9. Bg5 (9. exf5 $2 e4 10. Qe2
O-O $19) 9... f4 {Black manages to stabilize the position:} 10. g3 h6 11. Bxf6
Qxf6 $17) 7. Nd2 f5 8. Nb3 Qc7 (8... b6 {would be good from a strategical
point of view, yet we have to check what happens after} 9. dxc5 dxc5 10. Qd5 $5
Qc7 $1 (10... Qxd5 $2 11. cxd5 Nf6 12. c4 $16 {and White is clearly better due
to his pair of bishops and the strong pawn on d5.}) 11. Qxa8 Ne7 {Despite
being a rook down, Black is better since White will have to sacrifice material
to save his queen in some way.}) 9. Qh5+ g6 10. Qg5 b6 11. Be2 Qe7 12. h4 (12.
Qxe7+ Kxe7 {The endgame is very good for Black. For instance,} 13. a4 a5 {
We weaken b6, but a4 is also weak.} 14. O-O Nf6 15. Bd2 Be6 {With this move
and a later ...Rc8, we want to provoke d4-d5.} (15... Ba6 16. Rfe1 Nbd7 17.
Rab1 Rhc8 18. d5 Ne5 19. Na1 Rab8 20. Nc2 Bxc4 $19) 16. Rfd1 Nbd7 17. Be1 Rac8
18. d5 Bf7 $17 {Next, we put our knight on e5 and start playing on the
kingside.}) 12... Nd7 13. Ba3 Ba6 14. O-O-O O-O-O 15. Qf4 Ngf6 $17 {--> see
model game Ismagambetov,A (2497)-Volkov,S (2623) Moscow 2010.}) 6... dxe5 7.
Qd5 (7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Ba3 b6 9. Nf3 f6 {[%csl Ra3,Rc3,Rc4]} 10. Be2 Nc6 11.
Rd1+ Kc7 12. Nd2 Ba6 13. O-O Nge7 14. e4 Na5 15. f3 Rad8 16. Bc1 Nc8 17. Rfe1
Nd6 $19) 7... Qe7 8. Nf3 (8. Ba3 Nd7 ({Let's assume that for some reason} 8...
Na6 {is forced. However, even if we had to misplace our knight like this, we
manage to stabilize the position:} 9. Nf3 f6 10. Rb1 Rb8 {White has run out of
attacking moves and will be pushed back.} 11. Be2 Be6 12. Qd1 Nh6 13. O-O O-O
14. e4 Nf7 15. Qc2 Nd6 16. Nd2 Rbc8 17. Rfd1 b6 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Ya6b8,Yb8c6,
Yc6a5]}) 9. Nf3 Ngf6 10. Qd1 b6 {Black has managed to push the opponents queen
back and is starting to take over.}) 8... f6 (8... Nd7) (8... Nc6 $6 9. Ba3) 9.
Ba3 Na6 10. Rb1 Rb8 11. Rb5 b6 12. Rb1 Be6 13. Qc6+ Kf7 (13... Qd7) 14. Be2 Nh6
