1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Bb4 3. e3 $2 {It's surprising that a strong player plays this
bad move. Possibly Ismagambetov had no knowledge of this line.} Bxc3 4. bxc3 d6
5. d4 c5 $5 {The position resembles the Huebner Variation of the Nimzo-Indian.}
(5... Qe7) (5... Nc6) (5... Nd7) 6. Nf3 ({We have to calculate the
consequences of} 6. dxe5 dxe5 7. Qd5 {- White starts attacking our pawns and
we have to check if we can stabilize the position.} Qe7 8. Ba3 Nd7 ({Let's
assume that for some reason} 8... Na6 {is forced. However, even if we had to
misplace our knight like this, we manage to stabilize the position:} 9. Nf3 f6
10. Rb1 Rb8 {White has run out of attacking moves and will be pushed back.} 11.
Be2 Be6 12. Qd1 Nh6 13. O-O O-O 14. e4 Nf7 15. Qc2 Nd6 16. Nd2 Rbc8 17. Rfd1 b6
{[%csl Rc4][%cal Ya6b8,Yb8c6,Yc6a5]}) 9. Nf3 Ngf6 10. Qd1 b6 {Black has
managed to push the opponents queen back and is starting to take over.}) ({
After} 6. d5 {we play} f5 $1 {Compared to the Nimzo-Indian, our f-pawn can
advance immediately.} {For example} 7. Qh5+ g6 8. Qd1 Nf6 {White has provoked
the weakening or our dark squares, but he cannot exploit it since his
c1-bishop is shut in by the e3-pawn.} 9. f3 O-O ({Even the impressive} 9... Kd7
{[%csl Gc7][%cal Yd7c7] is playable.})) 6... e4 (6... Nc6 {was also possible.
For instance,} 7. Bd3 (7. dxc5 dxc5 8. Qd5 $2 Qa5 $1 $17 9. Bd2 Nf6 10. Qd6 Bf5
$17 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Ya8d8]}) 7... f5 8. e4 Nf6 $1 {Using a small tactic to
develop the pieces in the best way.} 9. Bg5 (9. exf5 $2 e4 10. Qe2 O-O $19)
9... f4 {Black manages to stabilize the position:} 10. g3 h6 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 $17)
7. Nd2 f5 8. Nb3 Qc7 (8... b6 {would be good from a strategical point of view,
yet we have to check what happens after} 9. dxc5 dxc5 10. Qd5 $5 Qc7 $1 (10...
Qxd5 $2 11. cxd5 Nf6 12. c4 $16 {and White is clearly better due to his pair
of bishops and the strong pawn on d5.}) 11. Qxa8 Ne7 {Despite being a rook
down, Black is better since White will have to sacrifice material to save his
queen in some way.}) 9. Qh5+ g6 10. Qg5 b6 11. Be2 Qe7 12. h4 (12. Qxe7+ Kxe7 {
The endgame is very good for Black. For instance,} 13. a4 a5 {We weaken b6,
but a4 is also weak.} 14. O-O Nf6 15. Bd2 Be6 {With this move and a later ...
Rc8, we want to provoke d4-d5.} (15... Ba6 16. Rfe1 Nbd7 17. Rab1 Rhc8 18. d5
Ne5 19. Na1 Rab8 20. Nc2 Bxc4 $19) 16. Rfd1 Nbd7 17. Be1 Rac8 18. d5 Bf7 $17 {
Next, we put our knight on e5 and start playing on the kingside.}) 12... Nd7
13. Ba3 Ba6 14. O-O-O O-O-O 15. Qf4 Ngf6 $17 16. Rhe1 Rhe8 17. Kc2 Qf7 18. Nd2
Qe6 19. Bf1 Nb8 20. f3 Qd7 21. Qg5 Qa4+ 22. Kb2 Nbd7 23. Qf4 Nh5 24. Qh2 Ndf6
25. g4 exf3 26. gxh5 Ng4 27. Qf4 f2 28. hxg6 hxg6 29. h5 fxe1=Q 30. Rxe1 gxh5
31. Bd3 Kc7 32. Bxf5 Bc8 33. Bc2 Qc6 34. Qg5 Qg2 35. Kc1 Nxe3 36. Qxh5 Nxc4 0-1

