1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Bb4 3. g3 Bxc3 4. dxc3 Ne7 ({A good alternative way of playing
the position:} 4... d6 5. Bg2 f5 (5... Nc6) 6. e4 (6. Nf3 Nf6 7. Bg5 Nbd7 (7...
h6 8. Bxf6 Qxf6)) 6... fxe4 7. Bxe4 Nf6 8. Bg5 O-O 9. Ne2 Nc6 $15) 5. Bg2 d6 6.
e4 Nbc6 7. Nf3 O-O 8. O-O {Now Black has two interesting plans: either to play
...f5 immediately or to try to first exchange the light-squared bishops and to
afterwards play ...f5.} Be6 $5 (8... f5 $5) 9. Qe2 f6 (9... h6 {Usually we
want to use this pawn to control g5, and then (after exchanging the
light-squared bishops) play f5 !} 10. Rd1 Qc8 {Stepping out of the line of the
rook and preparing ...Bh3.} 11. Nd2 Bg4 12. f3 Bh3 13. Bxh3 (13. Nf1 Bxg2 14.
Kxg2 f5 $17 ({14...f5 is very good, but I want to show another interesting
idea:} 14... Nd8 15. Ne3 Ne6 16. Nd5 Qe8 17. Be3 f5 {Âfter transferring our
knight to e6 we go for ...f5 after all.} 18. exf5 Nxf5 19. Bf2 Qf7 20. Rd2 Rae8
21. Rad1 {Now we can drive the knight from d5, using tactics:} c6 $1 22. Ne3
Nh4+ $1 $19)) 13... Qxh3 14. Nf1 f5 $17) 10. Rd1 Qc8 11. Nd2 Bg4 12. f3 Bh3 13.
Bxh3 Qxh3 14. Nf1 f5 {Black is following the same plan, that we have seen
after 9...h6.} 15. Qg2 Qh5 {Even the endgame would be good for Black, but it's
more promising to keep the queens on the board.} 16. Ne3 fxe4 (16... f4 $3 {
Stockfish} 17. g4 Qf7 18. Nd5 Ng6 19. Qf2 Nd8 $1 {Again this strong manoeuver
- the knight stands perfect on e6 and we can chase away the d5-knight at some
point.} 20. b3 Ne6 $17) 17. fxe4 {Black had a slight advantage, but too many
pieces were exchanged and she was unable to make progress.} Nd8 18. Bd2 Ne6 19.
Nd5 Rae8 20. Rf1 Nc8 21. h4 Rxf1+ (21... Nb6 22. Nxb6 axb6 23. Be3 Qg4 $17) 22.
Rxf1 Rf8 23. Rxf8+ Kxf8 24. Kf2 c6 (24... Nb6 25. Nxb6 axb6 26. Qf3+ Qxf3+ 27.
Kxf3 $11) (24... Ne7 25. Qf3+ Qxf3+ 26. Kxf3 c6 27. Nxe7 Kxe7 28. Be3 $15 {/=})
25. Ne3 Nc5 26. Qf3+ Qf7 27. Qxf7+ Kxf7 28. Kf3 g6 29. Nd1 Nb6 30. b3 Nbd7 31.
Be3 a6 32. Nf2 Ne6 33. Nd3 Ndc5 34. Ke2 Nxd3 35. Kxd3 h5 1/2-1/2

