1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Bb4 3. g3 Bxc3 4. bxc3 Nc6 5. Bg2 (5. c5 {is not a problem.} d5
(5... b6 6. Bg2 $5 (6. d4 $5) (6. cxb6 $2 axb6 {would be very good for Black.})
) 6. cxd6 cxd6 {Even though White has undoubled his pawns, Black's position is
totally playable.}) 5... d6 6. d3 f5 $1 (6... Nf6 $2 7. e4 $14) 7. Nf3 Nf6 8.
O-O (8. Bg5 O-O 9. O-O h6 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. Nd2 (11. Rb1 Rb8 12. Nd2 Bd7 13.
Re1 b6 14. Qa4 e4) 11... Bd7 12. Rb1 Rab8) 8... O-O 9. Rb1 Qe8 $1 {A very
important move! Black prepares an attack with ...Qh5, ...f4, ...Bh3 and also
makes ...b6 possible, which solves the problem of developing the c8-bishop.}
10. Nd2 (10. Bg5 b6 (10... Nh5 $5) 11. Bxf6 Rxf6 12. Nd2 Bd7 $15) 10... f4 $1 (
10... b6 $5 {was also very good. For example} 11. e4 f4 $1 12. gxf4 exf4 (12...
Nh5 $5 {can be another powerful idea:} 13. f5 (13. fxe5 Nf4) 13... g6 14. fxg6
Nf4 $17) 13. d4 Qg6 {Black's attack outweighs White's advantage in the center.
The central pawn "look good", but are immobile.} 14. Kh1 Bg4 15. f3 Bd7 16. Nb3
Nh5 17. Rg1 (17. d5 Ne5) 17... Ng3+ 18. hxg3 Qh5+ 19. Bh3 Qxh3#) 11. Ne4 (11.
gxf4 exf4 $17 (11... Nh5 12. fxe5 (12. e3 exf4 $15) 12... Nf4 $40)) 11... Qh5
12. e3 $2 Ng4 $1 ({Exchanging queens is of course out of the question.} 12...
Qxd1 $4 13. Rxd1 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 fxe3 15. Bxe3 $16) 13. h3 f3 $1 14. hxg4 Bxg4
15. Bh1 Rae8 $19 {White is powerless against Black's mating attack on the
h-file.} 16. Nd2 Re6 17. Nxf3 Rh6 0-1

