1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Bb4 3. g3 {I was very curious to see how this top GM would
treat the position. But he was just worse after a few moves!} Bxc3 4. dxc3 d6
5. Bg2 Nc6 6. Nf3 Nge7 7. O-O Be6 8. b3 h6 {It is necessary to cover g5 before
playing ...Qd7.} (8... Qd7 $2 9. Ng5 Bf5 10. e4 Bg4 11. f3 Bh5 12. Bh3 $14 {
[%csl Gh3,Rh5]}) 9. e4 Qd7 {Preparing ...Bh3.} 10. Re1 $1 {White prepares Bh1
in response to ...Bh3. White would be worse, if he allows the exchange of
light-squared bishops. For example,} (10. Be3 Bh3 11. Re1 Bxg2 12. Kxg2 f5 13.
exf5 Nxf5 14. Nd2 O-O 15. Ne4 Kh8 {Black is better - White's king is weak and
he has the better pawn structure. White's pawns are immobile, while it's
possible for Black to even play on the queenside (though he probably
shouldn't!):} 16. Qc2 a6 17. Rac1 b5 18. cxb5 axb5 $17) ({or} 10. Ne1 Bh3 11.
Nc2 Bxg2 12. Kxg2 O-O 13. Ne3 f5 14. exf5 Nxf5 15. Nd5 Nd8 16. Qd3 Ne6 17. Be3
Kh8 18. Rad1 Qf7 $17) 10... Bh3 11. Bh1 (11. Nd2 Bxg2 12. Kxg2 O-O 13. Nf1 Kh8
(13... f5 {is possible and even the best move. I just want to demonstrate some
ideas.}) 14. Ne3 f5 ({or} 14... Nd8 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Yd8e6]}) 15. exf5 Nxf5 16.
Nd5 Nce7 (16... Nd8 $3 17. Qd3 Ne6 18. Bd2 b6 19. Rad1 g5 20. Bc1 Qg7 21. Kg1
Rf7 22. Re2 Raf8 $17) 17. Qd3 Nxd5 18. cxd5 Rf7 $17 {We fixed White's pawn
structure, but the resulting position is still better for Black.}) 11... Bg4
12. Qd3 f5 13. exf5 Bxf5 14. Qe2 Bg4 15. Qd3 (15. c5 O-O 16. cxd6 cxd6 17. Ba3
Qe6 $3 $15 {Stockfish}) 15... O-O 16. Nd2 Rf7 (16... a5 17. Ne4 Nd8 18. Be3 Ne6
$15) 17. f3 $1 {An important move as otherwise I can prepare to play ...Bf3:} (
17. Ne4 $2 Raf8 18. Be3 Qf5 $17 (18... Bf3 $17)) 17... Bf5 18. Qe2 Raf8 19. Ne4
Kh8 ({Best was} 19... b6 $5 {, stopping any c4-c5.} 20. Be3 Nd8 21. Rad1 Qc8
22. b4 (22. Nf2 Bd7 $15 {[%cal Yd7c6]}) 22... Ne6 $15 (22... Be6 23. c5 $132))
20. Bd2 Ng8 21. Rf1 Nf6 22. Nf2 $1 ({In case of} 22. Bg2 $2 {I happily take on
e4} Nxe4 {, imposing a static pawn structure.} 23. fxe4 Bg4 24. Qd3 b6 $17 {
With two bad bishops for White!}) 22... Bg6 (22... Re7 23. Bg2 Qe8 24. Rae1 Qg6
25. Bc1 Bd7 26. Kh1 b6 27. Bd2 Nd8 28. Kg1 Bc6 $15) 23. Rae1 Bh5 24. Bg2 Qd8
25. Kh1 Qd7 26. Kg1 Qd8 27. Kh1 Qd7 28. Kg1 Qd8 1/2-1/2

