1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Bb4 3. Qc2 a5 $5 {Not the main move of course, but Carlsen
shows that White's setup does not contain any threats and Black can pretty
much play anything!} (3... Nf6) 4. g3 Nf6 5. Bg2 O-O 6. a3 $6 Bxc3 7. Qxc3 $2 (
7. dxc3 $2 a4 $17) (7. bxc3 $1 $132) 7... Re8 8. Nf3 (8. b3 c6 (8... Nc6 $15))
8... Nc6 (8... d5 $3 $17 {looks very strong as White cannot take on e5.} 9. d4
(9. Nxe5 $2 d4 $19 {[%csl Re5]}) 9... exd4 10. Nxd4 c5 11. Nb5 d4 $17) 9. d3 {
Now Black can choose between two good options: fixing the pawn structure on
the queenside and playing ...d5 - both moves are good.} a4 (9... d5 10. cxd5
Nxd5) 10. O-O h6 11. b4 axb3 12. Qxb3 e4 13. dxe4 Nxe4 $15 {White has the
bishop pair, but his pawn structure is worse.} 14. Bb2 d6 15. Rfd1 Qe7 16. Nd4
Nxd4 17. Rxd4 Nc5 18. Qc2 Qxe2 19. Rd2 Qh5 20. a4 Bf5 21. Qc3 Qg6 22. a5 Ne4
23. Bxe4 Bxe4 24. f3 Bc6 25. Kf2 Re5 26. Re2 Rxe2+ 27. Kxe2 f6 28. Kf2 Qf5 29.
