1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Bb4 3. Nd5 a5 4. a3 Bc5 {Our move is 4...Be7, but this is also
worth studying.} 5. e3 c6 6. Nc3 d6 7. d4 Ba7 8. Nf3 ({Black is not scared of} 
8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Nf3 f6 11. Be2 Be6 12. O-O Nd7 13. Rd1 Kc7) 8...
Nd7 9. Be2 Ngf6 (9... f5 {I tried to make this work, but it is too slow.} 10.
e4 $1 $16 (10. O-O Ngf6 11. b4 $14) 10... f4 11. c5 $1) 10. O-O O-O 11. b3 Bb8
(11... e4 12. Nd2 d5) 12. Bb2 (12. d5 Nc5 $11) 12... e4 13. Nd2 d5 {Black has
a good position. If his pawn were still on a6, he would be much better!} 14.
Re1 {This is slow and gives Black time to prepare his attack. White should
consider f3.} Re8 15. b4 Nf8 {We don't take on b4 as we don't want to open the
position on the queenside.} 16. g3 Ne6 17. Qb3 (17. h4 g5 18. hxg5 Nxg5 $19)
17... Ng5 $19 {Black's attack is already very strong.} 18. b5 Nh3+ 19. Kg2 h5
20. bxc6 bxc6 21. cxd5 cxd5 22. Na4 Bc7 23. Nc5 Rb8 24. Qc3 Ng4 25. Rf1 Qf6 26.
Rab1 Ngxf2 27. Bxh5 Qg5 28. Be2 Ng4 29. Bxg4 Qxg4 30. Rbe1 Ng5 31. Re2 Qxe2+
0-1

