1. c4 e5 2. g3 {This move order rules out any systems with ...Bb4. But by
committing himself to g3 very early on, Black gets other alternatives.} c6 {
Our suggested repertoire is based on this move - this reversed c3-Sicilian is
a popular way to meet 2.g3. We specifically pick the move order 2...c6 and not
2...Nf6 3.Bg2 c6 (which of course also fine), because we want to keep the
option of playing ...f5! After 2...c6, White's options are limited since Black
is ready to occupy the center with 3...d5.} (2... Nf6 3. Bg2 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 {
leads to the Reversed Dragon.}) (2... Nc6 3. Bg2 g6 {leads to the Reversed
Closed Sicilian.}) 3. Nf3 ({We meet} 3. d4 {in the spirit of the Bogo-Indian:}
Bb4+ (3... exd4 4. Qxd4 d5 {often leads to positions with an isolated d-pawn
for Black.}) (3... e4 $5 4. Bg2 d5 {gaining space in the center, is a popular
alternative. It's a good continuation, though more committal and theoretical
than 3...Bb4+.}) 4. Bd2 Bxd2+ 5. Qxd2 d6 {After exchanging the dark-squared
bishops, we put our central pawns on Black squares - a healthy strategy.}) 3...
d6 $5 {Much more rarely seen than 3...e4, but quite good!} (3... e4 4. Nd4 d5
5. cxd5 Qxd5 {is the theoretical main line.}) {After} 4. Nc3 {we will cover
two possible setups:} f5 $5 {followed by ...Nf6, ...Be7, ...0-0, ...h6, ...Be6,
...Nbd7 and if possible ...d5.} ({and the more solid} 4... Nf6 {followed by ...
Be7, ...0-0, ...h6, ...Be6, ...Nbd7 and if possible ...d5.}) *

