1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 $1 {A VERY INTERESTING LINE WITHOUT MUCH THEORY! Black is
already threatening ...d7-d5 with the better game, so there are only 2 good
moves for White here - 3.d4 and 3.Nf3.} (2... d6 3. Bg2 f5 {Now White can
still go for the powerful Botvinnik setup after both, 3...f5 and 3...Nf6:} (
3... Nf6 4. Nc3 Nc6 5. d3 Be7 6. e4 O-O 7. Nge2 a5 8. O-O $14 {White has three
possible plans: 1) Play f4 2) Prepare d4 with h3 and Be3 3) Prepare b4 with a3
and Rb1}) 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. d3 $1 Be7 6. e4 O-O 7. Nge2 $14) 3. Nf3 $1 {This is
the most critical line in the 2...c6 variation!} (3. d4 $5 Bb4+ $1 {We play
this good and practical system. The alternatives 3...e4 and 3...exd4 are more
difficult to learn.} 4. Bd2 (4. Nc3 e4 $1 5. Bg2 d5 $132) 4... Bxd2+ 5. Qxd2 d6
{Once we have exchanged the dark-squared bishops, we play ...d6.} 6. Nc3 (6.
dxe5 dxe5 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {Black is at least equal in this endgame.} 8. Nc3 f6 9.
Bg2 Kc7 10. Nf3 {White is ahead in development, but none of his developed
pieces is very effective. For example} Be6 11. b3 Ne7 12. O-O a5 13. Rfd1 Na6 {
and Black is already slightly better.}) 6... Nf6 $1 7. Bg2 (7. Nf3 $6 e4 $15 8.
Ng5 d5) ({Again, going for an endgame suits Black:} 7. dxe5 $6 dxe5 8. Qxd8+ $6
(8. Qg5 $6 O-O 9. Qxe5 Qb6 $1 $17 10. b3 Nbd7 $1 (10... Qxf2+) 11. Qf4 Re8 $17)
8... Kxd8 9. Bh3 Bxh3 10. Nxh3 Ke7 $132) (7. e4 O-O 8. Nge2 b5 $5 {--> see
model game Carlsen - Harikrishna.}) 7... O-O 8. e3 (8. e4 b5 $3 {This gambit
continuation works because White is behind in development.} (8... Nbd7 $1 {
is a good alternative.} 9. Nge2 a6 10. O-O (10. a4 $6 a5 $1) 10... b5 $132 {
Marin}) 9. dxe5 (9. cxb5 cxb5 10. Nxb5 Nc6 $44) 9... dxe5 10. Qxd8 Rxd8 11.
cxb5 cxb5 12. Nxb5 Nc6 $15) (8. Nf3 $2 e4 9. Ng5 d5 $15) (8. Rd1 Qe7 $132 {
In this position, resembling a Bogo-Indian, the control over the d-file has no
significance.} 9. dxe5 {This is often a strategical mistake.} dxe5 10. Qd6 Qxd6
11. Rxd6 {Black is at least equal in this endgame. For example,} Na6 12. Nf3
Re8 13. O-O Bg4 14. Rfd1 Nc5 15. h3 Bxf3 16. Bxf3 a5 {White cannot profit from
controlling the d-file. At the very least, Black manages to exchange rooks.}
17. e3 Kf8 18. Kf1 Ke7 19. Ke1 Red8 20. Rxd8 Rxd8 21. Rxd8 Kxd8 $11) 8... Re8
$1 9. Nge2 e4 $1 10. O-O (10. h3 Nbd7 $5 (10... Bf5 $2 {THIS IS TOTALLY WRONG
HERE, BECAUSE WHITE WILL GAIN SEVERAL TEMPI ON THE BISHOP, CASTLE LONG AND
ATTACK!} 11. g4 Bg6 12. Nf4 $16 Nbd7 13. O-O-O $16) (10... d5 $5) 11. g4 Nb6
12. b3 d5 13. c5 Nbd7 $15 14. Ng3 h6) (10. d5 c5 {Black controls d4 and aims
to put a knight on e5. For example} 11. O-O Bf5 12. h3 h6 (12... h5 $5) 13. g4
Bh7 14. Ng3 Nbd7) 10... Nbd7 $1 (10... d5 {Maybe this is slightly premature.}
11. cxd5 cxd5 12. f3 exf3 13. Rxf3 {I don't like that White can create
pressure on the f-file and the d5-pawn.}) (10... Bf5 $5 11. h3 h6 $1 {SUPER
SOS ! Usually, when Isee h3 in such positions, I go ...h6!}) 11. Rac1 {Now
Black has a very interesting idea:} Nb6 $1 12. b3 d5 $132 13. c5 $2 (13. cxd5
Nbxd5 $11) 13... Nbd7 14. b4 Nf8 15. b5 h5 $15) (3. Nc3 d5 $1 (3... Bb4 $5 4.
Bg2 d6 $132) 4. d4 dxc4 (4... Bb4 $5 5. dxe5 (5. cxd5 Qxd5 6. Nf3 e4 $15 {
For example:} 7. Nd2 Qxd4 8. Bg2 f5 9. O-O Be6 10. Qc2 Nf6) 5... d4 6. a3 Ba5
7. b4 dxc3 8. bxa5 Qxa5 9. Qc2 Ne7) 5. dxe5 Qxd1+ 6. Nxd1 Bb4+ 7. Bd2 Bxd2+ 8.
Kxd2 Be6 9. f4 f6 $13) (3. Bg2 $6 {This is already too slow.} d5 4. cxd5 cxd5
5. d4 e4 6. f3 (6. Nc3 $6 Bb4 $1 7. Bd2 Bxc3 $3 (7... Nc6 8. f3 $132) 8. Bxc3
Nf6 $1 $15 (8... Nc6 $2 9. Bxe4 $3 $16) 9. e3 Nc6 10. Ne2 O-O 11. O-O a5 (11...
Bf5 $17) 12. Qd2 b6 $17) 6... Bb4+ 7. Bd2 Bxd2+ 8. Qxd2 f5 $1 $132) (3. Qa4 {
An idea known from the c3-Sicilian. It gives nothing special for White. Black
has several options, all of them leading to equal chances.} Nf6 (3... Bc5) (
3... Na6)) 3... d6 $5 {This is a rare but very interesting line of the English
Opening! SOS! I play ...c6-d6-f5 ONLY after I see a knight on f3. By that, I
have avoided the famous Botvinnik setup with c4-Nc3-d3-e4!-Nge2!-g3-Bg2.} 4.
Nc3 (4. Bg2 f5 $1 5. O-O Nf6 {and we will soon transpose to the main line.} 6.
Nc3 Be7) (4. e4 $5 Bg4 $1 (4... c5 $5 {This is also simple and good. We lose a
tempo, but will develop our knight to e7, keeping f5 as an option. White needs
to retreat with his knight , in order to go for f4. Still, the line with 4...
Bg4! is far more interesting!} 5. Bg2 Nc6 6. O-O g6 7. Nc3 Bg7 8. d3 Nge7 9.
Nh4 (9. a3 O-O 10. Rb1 a5 11. Ne1 Nd4 12. b4 axb4 13. axb4 b6 14. Nc2 (14. f4
exf4) 14... Nxc2 15. Qxc2 Nc6 $132) 9... O-O 10. f4 exf4 $132) (4... f5 $2 5.
exf5 Bxf5 6. d4 e4 7. Nh4 $16) 5. Bg2 h5 $3 {The passion of the new engines to
move their h- and a- pawns!} 6. h3 (6. h4 Nd7 7. Nc3 Ngf6 (7... Qf6 8. d3 Be7
9. O-O Bd8 $132 10. b4 Bb6) 8. d3 g6 $132) (6. d4 h4 $1 $132 7. dxe5 $6 Bxf3 (
7... hxg3 $3 8. hxg3 Rxh1+ 9. Bxh1 Nd7 $3 10. exd6 Qa5+ 11. Nc3 Qh5 12. Bg2
O-O-O $19 13. Be3) 8. Qxf3 dxe5 $15) 6... Bxf3 7. Bxf3 (7. Qxf3 h4 8. d3 Na6
$36 9. Nc3 Nc5 10. O-O Be7 11. Qe2 Ne6 12. Be3 Bg5 $15 13. f4 $2 Bh6 $3 $19 14.
f5 Nd4 15. Bxd4 exd4 16. Nd1 hxg3) 7... h4 8. g4 Be7 9. d4 Bg5 $3 $15) (4. d4
$2 e4 5. Ng5 (5. Nh4 d5 $15) (5. Nfd2 f5) 5... d5 $15) 4... f5 $1 {Another
very interesting system is to avoid ...f5 and play ...Nf6-Be7-0-0-h6!-Be6-Nbd7
and d5! ( IN FACT THIS SYSTEM IS EVEN EASIER TO LEARN !). BOTH VARIATIONS -
WITH OR WITHOUT ...f5 - ARE MOSTLY BASED ON PLANS!} (4... Nf6 $1 5. Bg2 Be7 6.
d3 O-O 7. O-O h6 $1 8. e4 $1 {This appears to be the only good try for White!
However, most players will go for a plan with b4:} (8. Bd2 $6 {Now...the plan
with b4 is very slow and Black is taking over the initiative!} Be6 9. b4 Nbd7
$15 10. b5 d5 $17 11. bxc6 bxc6 12. cxd5 cxd5) (8. Rb1 Be6 9. b4 Nbd7 $15 10.
e4 (10. b5 d5 $15) 10... d5 $1) (8. b4 Be6 9. b5 Nbd7 $15 {[%cal Yd6d5]}) 8...
c5 $1 (8... Be6 9. b3 c5 (9... Nbd7 10. d4 $16) 10. Ne1 Nc6 11. f4 Nd4 12. f5
Bd7 {Black has counterplay with ...b5 on the queenside and can defend with ...
Nh7 if White advances his g-pawn.}) 9. Nh4 (9. Nd5 Nxd5 10. cxd5 Bg4 (10... f5)
11. h3 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 Bg5 $1 $132) 9... Nc6 10. f4 (10. Nf5 Nd4 $132 (10... a6
11. f4 b5 $132)) 10... Nd4 $1 11. f5 (11. Be3 $4 exf4 $19 12. Rxf4 (12. gxf4
Ng4 $19) 12... g5) 11... b5 $3 12. cxb5 Bd7 13. a4 a6 $15) 5. Bg2 (5. e4 $6
fxe4 $3 6. Nxe4 Nf6 7. Nxf6+ Qxf6 8. d3 (8. Bg2 e4 $5 (8... c5 $5 9. d3 Be7 10.
O-O Nc6) 9. Qe2 d5 $132 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. d3 Bg4 $1 12. dxe4 Bb4+ 13. Kf1 O-O
14. Bf4 Nc6 15. e5 Qf7 $40 (15... Qg6 $40)) 8... Bg4 9. Bg2 Nd7 10. h3 Bh5 $132
) (5. d4 $6 e4 6. Ng5 Nf6 $1 (6... Be7 $1 7. h4 Nf6 8. Nh3 O-O 9. Nf4 Na6 $11 {
[%cal Ya6c7,Yd6d5]} 10. a3 Nc7 11. d5 Nd7 12. f3 exf3 13. exf3 Bf6 14. Bd2 Re8+
15. Kf2 Ne5 16. Nh5 Be7 17. Kg2 c5 18. Nf4 Bf8 19. b3 g6 20. Nh3 Nf7 21. Qc2
Qf6 22. Bd3 Bh6 23. Ng5 Ne5 24. Be2 Bg7 25. Rae1 h6 26. Nh3 Nf7 27. h5 g5 28.
f4 g4 29. Nf2 Bd7 30. Bd3 Rf8 31. Ncd1 Nh8 32. Nxg4 fxg4 33. Bc3 Qd8 34. Bh7+
Kf7 35. Qg6+ Nxg6 36. hxg6# {1-0 Shyam,N-Pranav,V/Dubai UAE 2019}) 7. Nh3 (7.
Bg2 d5 $132 8. cxd5 (8. Qb3 $6 h6 $1 9. Nh3 g5 $15 10. f3 dxc4 11. Qxc4 exf3
12. exf3 Qe7+ 13. Kf2 Be6 $15 14. Qa4 Nbd7 15. Re1 Nb6 16. Qc2 O-O-O $17) 8...
cxd5 9. O-O $2 (9. Nh3 $1 Bb4 $1 10. Bg5 Bxc3+ (10... O-O) 11. bxc3 O-O 12. Nf4
h6 13. Bxf6 Rxf6 14. Qb3 Rd6 15. O-O Nc6 $36) 9... h6 10. Nh3 g5 11. f3 Nc6 $17
12. fxe4 dxe4 $17 (12... fxe4 $17)) 7... d5 8. cxd5 Nxd5 $11 9. Nf4 Nxf4 10.
Bxf4 Bd6 11. e3 Bxf4 (11... O-O $6 12. Qb3+ Kh8 13. O-O-O $36) 12. gxf4 Be6 $11
) (5. d3 Nf6) 5... Nf6 6. O-O (6. d4 e4 7. Nh4 d5) 6... Be7 {This is the basic
position of the ...c6-d6-f5 system against 2.g3 c6 3.Nf3. YOU DONT HAVE TO
MEMORIZE THE LINES STARTING FROM HERE. YOU JUST NEED TO UNDERSTAND HOW WE
DEVELOP OUR PIECES DEPENDING ON WHITE'S SET UP!} (6... e4 $2 {would be a
mistake as we cannot keep the pawn on e4.} 7. Ne1 (7. Nh4) 7... Be7 8. d3 $1
exd3 9. Nxd3 $16 {[%csl Rd6,Rf5] Here our pawn on f5 does not make sense.}) 7.
d3 $5 (7. b3 O-O 8. e3 a5 $1 (8... e4 9. Nd4 d5 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. Bb2 {0-1 (52)
Vakhidov,J-Lorparizangeneh,S/Moscow RUS 2017} Nc6 $11) (8... Kh8 $5 9. d3 Be6
10. Bb2 Nbd7 11. Qc2 Qe8 12. b4 h6 (12... Rc8 $1 13. a4 d5 $36 (13... h6 14. a5
g5)) 13. b5 g5) 9. Bb2 Na6 10. d3 Be6 11. a3 Bf7 12. Qc2 (12. Ng5 Bh5) 12...
Nd7 13. Rab1 Nc7 14. b4 axb4 15. axb4 d5 $36 (15... Bh5 16. b5 Ne6 17. Nd2 Rc8
$132)) (7. d4 e4 8. Nh4 (8. Ng5 d5 (8... h6 $6 9. Nh3 g5 10. d5 $36 {[%cal
Yf2f3]}) 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. Nh3 O-O 11. Bg5 Be6 $11 {[%cal Yb8c6]}) 8... Nh5 $5 (
8... O-O 9. f3 exf3 10. Nxf3 Na6 $132) (8... Rg8 $5 {--> see model game Najart
- Chakravarthi}) 9. f3 f4 $132) (7. b4 O-O 8. d3 Kh8 (8... Qe8 9. b5) (8... h6
{[%cal Yc8e6,Yb8d7]}) (8... a6 9. a4 Kh8 10. Bd2 Be6 11. b5 Nbd7) 9. Bd2 Na6
10. Rb1 Bd7 11. b5 Nc5) 7... a5 $1 {This is probably better than ...0-0. HERE
ARE SOME SAMPLE LINES, DEMONSTRATING TYPICAL IDEAS FOR BOTH SIDES. Once again:
no need to memorize much!} 8. Rb1 ({If White develops quietly with} 8. b3 O-O
9. Bb2 {we can choose between different plans: 1) ...Qe8-h5 2) ...h6, ...Be6, .
..Nbd7, and possibly ...d5 3) ...Na6} Na6 $132 (9... h6 10. a3 Be6 11. b4 Nbd7
12. b5 d5) (9... Qe8) 10. a3 f4 $132 (10... Qe8)) (8. c5 $5 O-O 9. cxd6 (9. e4
fxe4 10. dxe4 Na6 $132 11. cxd6 Bxd6 12. h3 (12. Be3 Qe7 $132) 12... b5 $132)
9... Qxd6 10. e4 (10. Bd2 Kh8 $132 11. Qc2 Na6 12. a3 Be6 13. Rfd1 Qc7) (10. d4
$5 e4 11. Bf4 (11. Ne5 Be6 12. f3 c5 $17 (12... exf3 13. Nxf3 Nd5)) 11... Qd8
12. Qb3+ (12. Ne5 Be6) 12... Nd5 13. Ne5 Ra6 $5 (13... a4 $5 14. Nxa4 Be6 15.
Qd1 Nxf4 16. gxf4 Rf6) 14. Nxd5 cxd5 15. Rfc1 Nc6) 10... fxe4 11. dxe4 Qxd1 (
11... Bg4 12. Qb3+) 12. Rxd1 Bg4 (12... Nbd7 13. h3 Re8 14. b3 Bf8 15. Bb2 Nc5
$11) 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Na6 $11 15. Kg2 (15. Be3 Bc5 $15) (15. Bd2 Bc5 16.
Kg2 Bd4 $132) 15... Bc5 16. Rb1 b5 $132 17. b3 (17. Bd2 Nc7 (17... a4) 18. Rbc1
Ne6 19. Be1 a4 $36) 17... Nc7 $36) (8. Bd2 $5 {SOS !! when white is going for
a quick a3-b4, a good way to play is to strike in the center with d5....after
Be6!-h6! and d5!} O-O 9. a3 (9. Rb1 Qe8 10. a3 Qh5 11. b4 axb4 12. axb4 Be6 (
12... f4 13. gxf4)) 9... Be6 10. b4 h6 $5 11. Qc2 (11. Rb1 axb4 12. axb4 Nbd7
13. Nh4 $6 Qe8 14. b5 Rc8 $15 15. bxc6 bxc6 16. Qc2 d5 (16... Qh5 $15) (16...
g5 17. Nf3 f4 $15)) 11... Nbd7 12. Rab1 axb4 13. axb4 d5 $15) (8. e4 $5 fxe4 9.
dxe4 Na6 $132 (9... O-O $132)) 8... O-O 9. a3 Be6 10. b4 (10. Bd2 h6 $1 {
Again, we follow the same plan: ...Be6-h6!-Nbd7, and ...d5!} 11. e3 (11. b4
axb4 12. axb4 (12. Rxb4 Bc8 $15) 12... Nbd7 13. b5 (13. Nh4 $6 Qe8) 13... d5 (
13... Rc8)) 11... Nbd7 12. Qc2 Qe8 $15 (12... g5 $15) (12... d5) 13. b4 axb4
14. axb4 e4 $17 15. Nd4 exd3 16. Qxd3 Ne5 $19) (10. Ng5 Bd7 11. b4 axb4 12.
axb4 h6 13. Nf3 Be6 14. b5 Nbd7 {[%cal Yd6d5]}) 10... axb4 11. axb4 h6 $1 12.
b5 (12. Bb2 Nbd7 13. b5 Qe8 14. bxc6 bxc6 15. Nd2 Rc8 $132) (12. Nh4 Qe8 13. b5
g5 (13... d5) 14. Nf3 Nbd7 $132) 12... Qe8 13. Bd2 Nbd7 14. Qc2 Rc8 $1 15. Rfc1
Qh5 $36 (15... f4 $132) *

