1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. d4 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Bxd2+ 5. Qxd2 d6 6. dxe5 dxe5 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8
8. Nc3 (8. Nf3 f6 9. Nc3 Be6 10. O-O-O+ Kc7 11. e3 Nd7 12. Be2 Nh6) 8... Kc7 9.
b3 Nf6 ({I generally prefer} 9... f6 {in such positions.}) 10. f3 ({Maybe
Black's idea was to provoke} 10. Nf3 {when White no longer can play Bh3. A
possible continuation:} Re8 11. Ng5 Re7 12. Bh3 h6 $3 {In such position we
usually like to exchange our light-squared bishop for a knight.} (12... Bxh3
13. Nxh3 Nbd7 $15) 13. Bxc8 hxg5 14. Bh3 a5 $17 15. O-O-O Na6 16. Rd2 Nc5 17.
Bg2 {White cannot double his rooks yet, because we threaten ...Rh8.} (17. Rhd1
Rh8) 17... Rd7 {Exchanging one pair of rooks reduces White's counterplay.} 18.
Rhd1 Rxd2 19. Rxd2 g4 {[%cal Ya8h8] We keep one pair of rooks on the board -
our rook will be very useful, while White's rook does nothing on the d-file.}
20. h3 gxh3 21. Bxh3 Rh8 22. Bf1 Rh2) 10... a5 11. Rd1 Na6 {It's better to
develop the knight to a6 instead of d7. From a6 it can go to c5 and in some
cases b4, while it does not block the c8-bishop.} 12. e3 Nc5 $17 13. e4 h5 (
13... g5 $1 $17) 14. h4 $15 ({White should not allow ...h4.} 14. Nge2 h4 15. g4
Nh7 16. h3 Ng5 $17 {[%csl Rf1,Gg5]}) 14... Ne6 15. Nh3 Nh7 16. Kf2 f6 17. Ke3
Nd4 18. Ne2 Nxe2 19. Bxe2 Nf8 20. f4 Bxh3 21. Rxh3 Ne6 22. Rf1 Kd6 23. fxe5+
fxe5 24. Rf7 b6 25. Rh1 Raf8 26. Rd1+ Kc5 27. Re7 Rf6 28. a3 Rhh6 29. Rd3 a4
30. b4+ Kxc4 31. Rd6+ Kb3 32. Rxc6 Kxa3 33. Rxb6 Kb2 34. Ra6 a3 35. Rea7 Nd4
36. Ra4 Rc6 37. Bd1 Rc3+ 38. Kd2 Rf6 39. b5 Rf2+ 40. Ke1 Rh2 41. b6 Nc2+ 42.
Kf1 Ne3+ 43. Kg1 Rg2+ 44. Kh1 Rd2 45. Rb4+ Ka1 46. Rc7 Rxd1+ 47. Kh2 Ng4+ 48.
Kg2 Rxc7 49. bxc7 Rc1 50. Rb7 Rc2+ 51. Kf1 Nf6 0-1

